{"title_page": "Potnia Theron", "text_new": "[[File:Artemis, Parian pottery plate, 675-600 BC, AM Mykonos, 177233.jpg|thumb|[[Artemis]] as Mistress of Animals, [[Paros|Parian]] pottery, 675-600 BC]]\n[[File:Museum of Anatolian Civilizations 1320259 nevit.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Seated Woman of \u00c7atalh\u00f6y\u00fck|Seated woman of \u00c7atalh\u00f6y\u00fck]] flanked by two [[Lion|lionesses]]]]\n\nThe '''Potnia Theron''' ({{Lang-grc|\u1f29 \u03a0\u03cc\u03c4\u03bd\u03b9\u03b1 \u0398\u03b7\u03c1\u1ff6\u03bd}}, {{IPA-grc|h\u025b\u02d0 p\u00f3t.ni.a t\u02b0\u025b\u02d0.r\u0254&#770;\u02d0n|}}, <small>lit.</small> \"The Animal Mistress\") or '''Mistress of Animals''' is a widespread [[motif (visual arts)|motif]] in ancient art from the Mediterranean world and the [[ancient Near East]], showing a central human, or human-like, female figure who grasps two animals, one to each side. The oldest such depiction, the [[Seated Woman of \u00c7atalh\u00f6y\u00fck]], is a clay sculpture from [[\u00c7atalh\u00f6y\u00fck]] in modern Turkey, made c 6,000 BC. This motif is more common in later Near Eastern and [[Mesopotamian art]] with a male figure, called the [[Master of Animals]].\n\nAlthough the connections between images and concepts in the various ancient cultures concerned remain very unclear, such images are often referred to by the Greek term ''Potnia Theron'' regardless of culture of origin. The term is first used once by [[Homer]] as a descriptor of [[Artemis]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.01.0133:book=21:card=468|title=Homer, Iliad, Book 21, line 468|last=|first=|date=|website=Perseus Digital Library|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13|quote=T\u1f78\u03bd \u03b4\u1f72 \u03ba\u03b1\u03c3\u03b9\u03b3\u03bd\u03ae\u03c4\u03b7 \u03bc\u03ac\u03bb\u03b1 \u03bd\u03b5\u03af\u03ba\u03b5\u03c3\u03b5 \u03c0\u03cc\u03c4\u03bd\u03b9\u03b1 \u03b8\u03b7\u03c1\u1ff6\u03bd \u1f0c\u03c1\u03c4\u03b5\u03bc\u03b9\u03c2 \u1f00\u03b3\u03c1\u03bf\u03c4\u03ad\u03c1\u03b7, \u03ba\u03b1\u1f76 \u1f40\u03bd\u03b5\u03af\u03b4\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf\u03bd \u03c6\u03ac\u03c4\u03bf \u03bc\u1fe6\u03b8\u03bf\u03bd...}}</ref> and often used to describe female divinities associated with animals.<ref name=fatd>{{cite book|last=Fischer-Hansen|first=Tobias|title=From Artemis to Diana: the goddess of man and beast|year=2009|publisher=Museum Tusculanum Press|isbn=978-8763507882 |author2=Birte Poulsen|page=23}}</ref> The word ''[[Potnia]]'', meaning mistress or lady, was a [[Mycenaean Greek]] word inherited by [[ancient Greek|Classical Greek]], with the same meaning, cognate to [[Sanskrit]] ''{{IAST|patn\u012b}}.''<ref>{{cite book|last=Chadwick|first=John|title=The Mycenaean world|year=1976|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-29037-1|page=[https://archive.org/details/mycenaeanworld00chad/page/92 92]|url=https://archive.org/details/mycenaeanworld00chad/page/92}}</ref>\n\nHomer's mention of Potnia Theron refers to Artemis; [[Walter Burkert]] describes this mention as \"a well established formula\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Burkert|first=Walter|title=Greek Religion|year=1987|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=978-0-674-36281-9|page=149}}</ref> An Artemis-type deity, a \"Mistress of the Animals\", is often assumed to have existed in prehistoric religion and often referred to as Potnia Theron with some scholars positing a relationship between Artemis and goddesses depicted in [[Minoan art]].<ref name=fatd /><ref>{{cite book|last=Roller|first=Lynn E.|title=In search of god the mother: the cult of Anatolian Cybele|year=1999|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-21024-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/insearchofgodmot00roll/page/139 139]|quote=indefinite figures such as the Potnia Theron|url=https://archive.org/details/insearchofgodmot00roll/page/139}}</ref>\n\nAn early example of Italian ''Potnia ther\u00f2n'' is in the Museo civico archeologico di Monte Rinaldo <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.retemusealedeisibillini.it/monterinaldo/|title=Monte Rinaldo - Rete Museale dei Sibillini|website=Retemusealedeisibillini.it|accessdate=11 April 2018}}</ref> in Italy: a plate illustrates a goddess that wears a [[Peplos|long dress]] and holds hands with two [[Lion|lionesses]].\n\nIn the [[Aeneid]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=urn:cts:latinLit:phi0690.phi003.perseus-lat1:3.90-3.120|title=Virgil, Aeneid Book 3, lines 110-113|website=Perseus Digital Library|url-status=live}}</ref> Virgil mentions that inside of [[Psychro_Cave|Psychro's Cave]], in Crete, lived the goddess [[Cybele]] whose chariot was drawn by two lions.\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Pithos 102972x.jpg|Goddess flanked by two lionesses on a Knossos [[pithos]] \nFile:Emprunte d'un sceau de Cnossos.jpg|Minoan goddess flanked by two lionesses (note the tufted tails)\nFile:NAMA Art\u00e9mis Orthia.jpg|[[Artemis Orthia]] in the usual stance of ''Potnia Theron'' on an archaic ivory [[ex-voto|votive offering]], ([[National Archaeological Museum of Athens]])\n\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Potniai theron}}\n\n*[[Inara (goddess)]]\n*[[Iphigenia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Animal goddesses]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sources on Greek mythology]]\n[[Category:Artemis]]\n[[Category:Greek goddesses]]\n[[Category:Iconography]]\n[[Category:Minoan religion]]\n[[Category:Women in art]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Artemis, Parian pottery plate, 675-600 BC, AM Mykonos, 177233.jpg|thumb|[[Artemis]] as Mistress of Animals, [[Paros|Parian]] pottery, 675-600 BC]]\n[[File:Museum of Anatolian Civilizations 1320259 nevit.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Seated Woman of \u00c7atalh\u00f6y\u00fck|Seated woman of \u00c7atalh\u00f6y\u00fck]] flanked by two [[Lion|lionesses]]]]\n\nThe '''Potnia Theron''' ({{Lang-grc|\u1f29 \u03a0\u03cc\u03c4\u03bd\u03b9\u03b1 \u0398\u03b7\u03c1\u1ff6\u03bd}}, {{IPA-grc|h\u025b\u02d0 p\u00f3t.ni.a t\u02b0\u025b\u02d0.r\u0254&#770;\u02d0n|}}, <small>lit.</small> \"The Animal Mistress\") or '''Mistress of Animals''' is a widespread [[motif (visual arts)|motif]] in ancient art from the Mediterranean world and the [[ancient Near East]], showing a central human, or human-like, female figure who grasps two animals, one to each side. The oldest such depiction, the [[Seated Woman of \u00c7atalh\u00f6y\u00fck]], is a clay sculpture from [[\u00c7atalh\u00f6y\u00fck]] in modern Turkey, made c 6,000 BC. This motif is more common in later Near Eastern and [[Mesopotamian art]] with a male figure, called the [[Master of Animals]].\n\nAlthough the connections between images and concepts in the various ancient cultures concerned remain very unclear, such images are often referred to by the Greek term ''Potnia Theron'' regardless of culture of origin. The term is first used once by [[Homer]] as a descriptor of [[Artemis]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.01.0133:book=21:card=468|title=Homer, Iliad, Book 21, line 468|last=|first=|date=|website=Perseus Digital Library|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13|quote=T\u1f78\u03bd \u03b4\u1f72 \u03ba\u03b1\u03c3\u03b9\u03b3\u03bd\u03ae\u03c4\u03b7 \u03bc\u03ac\u03bb\u03b1 \u03bd\u03b5\u03af\u03ba\u03b5\u03c3\u03b5 \u03c0\u03cc\u03c4\u03bd\u03b9\u03b1 \u03b8\u03b7\u03c1\u1ff6\u03bd \u1f0c\u03c1\u03c4\u03b5\u03bc\u03b9\u03c2 \u1f00\u03b3\u03c1\u03bf\u03c4\u03ad\u03c1\u03b7, \u03ba\u03b1\u1f76 \u1f40\u03bd\u03b5\u03af\u03b4\u03b5\u03b9\u03bf\u03bd \u03c6\u03ac\u03c4\u03bf \u03bc\u1fe6\u03b8\u03bf\u03bd...}}</ref> and often used to describe female divinities associated with animals.<ref name=fatd>{{cite book|last=Fischer-Hansen|first=Tobias|title=From Artemis to Diana: the goddess of man and beast|year=2009|publisher=Museum Tusculanum Press|isbn=978-8763507882 |author2=Birte Poulsen|page=23}}</ref> The word ''[[Potnia]]'', meaning mistress or lady, was a [[Mycenaean Greek]] word inherited by [[ancient Greek|Classical Greek]], with the same meaning, cognate to [[Sanskrit]] ''{{IAST|patn\u012b}}.''<ref>{{cite book|last=Chadwick|first=John|title=The Mycenaean world|year=1976|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-29037-1|page=[https://archive.org/details/mycenaeanworld00chad/page/92 92]|url=https://archive.org/details/mycenaeanworld00chad/page/92}}</ref>\n\nHomer's mention of Potnia Theron refers to Artemis; [[Walter Burkert]] describes this mention as \"a well established formula\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Burkert|first=Walter|title=Greek Religion|year=1987|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=978-0-674-36281-9|page=149}}</ref> An Artemis-type deity, a \"Mistress of the Animals\", is often assumed to have existed in prehistoric religion and often referred to as Potnia Theron with some scholars positing a relationship between Artemis and goddesses depicted in [[Minoan art]].<ref name=fatd /><ref>{{cite book|last=Roller|first=Lynn E.|title=In search of god the mother: the cult of Anatolian Cybele|year=1999|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-21024-0|page=[https://archive.org/details/insearchofgodmot00roll/page/139 139]|quote=indefinite figures such as the Potnia Theron|url=https://archive.org/details/insearchofgodmot00roll/page/139}}</ref>\n\nAn early example of Italian ''Potnia ther\u00f2n'' is in the Museo civico archeologico di Monte Rinaldo <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.retemusealedeisibillini.it/monterinaldo/|title=Monte Rinaldo - Rete Museale dei Sibillini|website=Retemusealedeisibillini.it|accessdate=11 April 2018}}</ref> in Italy: a plate illustrates a goddess that wears a [[Peplos|long dress]] and holds hands with two [[Lion|lionesses]].\n\nIn the [[Aeneid]],<ref>{{cite book|title=Virgil, Aeneid Book 3, lines 110-113|url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=urn:cts:latinLit:phi0690.phi003.perseus-lat1:3.90-3.120}}</ref> Virgil mentions that inside of [[Psychro_Cave|Psychro's Cave]], in Crete, lived the goddess [[Cybele]] whose chariot was drawn by two lions.\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Pithos 102972x.jpg|Goddess flanked by two lionesses on a Knossos [[pithos]] \nFile:Emprunte d'un sceau de Cnossos.jpg|Minoan goddess flanked by two lionesses (note the tufted tails)\nFile:NAMA Art\u00e9mis Orthia.jpg|[[Artemis Orthia]] in the usual stance of ''Potnia Theron'' on an archaic ivory [[ex-voto|votive offering]], ([[National Archaeological Museum of Athens]])\n\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Potniai theron}}\n\n*[[Inara (goddess)]]\n*[[Iphigenia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Animal goddesses]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sources on Greek mythology]]\n[[Category:Artemis]]\n[[Category:Greek goddesses]]\n[[Category:Iconography]]\n[[Category:Minoan religion]]\n[[Category:Women in art]]\n", "name_user": "Mmick66", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Potnia_Theron"}
{"title_page": "Lingaraja Temple", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Lingaraj|activist|Lingaraj Azad}}\n{{short description|Hindu temple in Bhubaneswar, Odisha}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox Hindu temple\n| name               = Lingaraja Temple\n| native_name =\n| native_name_lang = or\n| image              = Beauty of LingrajTemple.jpg\n| caption            =\n| map_type        = <!-- India Odisha -->\n| map_caption        = Location in Odisha\n| coordinates        = {{coord|20|14|18|N|85|50|01|E|type:landmark_region:IN|display=inline,title}}\n| country            = India\n| state     = [[Odisha]]\n| district           = [[Khurda]]\n| locale             = Lingaraja Temple Road, Old Town, [[Bhubaneshwar]]\n| elevation_m        =\n| tradition = Saivism\n| deity      = [[Shiva]] As [[Shiva|Lingaraja]], [[Shiva|Adi Shiva]], [[Shiva|Adidev]] ([[Shiva|Maheswara]], [[Shiva|Tribhuvaneshwara]], [[Shiva|Bhubaneswar]]), \n[[Vishnu]] As [[Vishnu|Adi Narayana]], ([[Harihara]]) <br />\n[[Bhuvaneshvari]] Form of [[Parvati]] (consort)\n| festivals= [[Shivaratri]]\n| architecture       = [[Kalinga Architecture]]\n| temple_quantity  =\n| monument_quantity=\n| inscriptions       =\n| year_completed         = 11th century CE\n| creator            = Jajati Keshari\n| website            = http://www.lordlingaraj.org.in/\n}}\n{{Saivism}}\n'''Lingaraja Temple''' is a [[Hindu temple]] dedicated to [[Shiva]] and is one of the oldest temples in [[Bhubaneswar]], the capital of the Indian state of [[Odisha]]. The temple is the most prominent landmark of Bhubaneswar city and one of the major tourist attractions of the state.<ref name=\"Bhubaneswar Corporation\"/><ref name=\"ASI\"/><ref>{{cite book|title=India through the ages|url=https://archive.org/details/indiathroughages00mada|last=Gopal|first=Madan|year= 1990| page= [https://archive.org/details/indiathroughages00mada/page/175 175]|editor=K.S. Gautam|publisher=Publication Division, Ministry of Information and Broadcasting, Government of India}}</ref>\n\nThe Lingaraja temple is the largest temple in Bhubaneswar. The central tower of the temple is {{cvt|180|ft|m}} tall. The temple represents the quintessence of the [[Kalinga architecture]] and culminating the medieval stages of the architectural tradition at Bhubaneswar.<ref name=\"Ramesh Prasad Mohapatra 1986 Page 69\"/> The temple is believed to be built by the kings from the [[Somava\u1e43\u015b\u012b dynasty|Somavamsi dynasty]], with later additions from the [[Eastern Ganga dynasty|Ganga]] rulers. The temple is built in the ''[[Deula]]'' style that has four components namely, ''[[vimana]]'' (structure containing the sanctum), ''[[jagamohana]]'' (assembly hall), ''natamandira'' (festival hall) and ''bhoga-mandapa'' (hall of offerings), each increasing in the height to its predecessor. The temple complex has 50 other shrines and is enclosed by a large compound wall.\n\nBhubaneswar is called the Ekamra Kshetra as the deity of Lingaraja was originally under a mango tree (Ekamra) as noted in ''Ekamra Purana'', a 13th-century [[Sanskrit]] treatise. The temple is active in worship practises, unlike most other temples in Bhubaneswar and Shiva is worshipped as [[Harihara]], a combined form of Vishnu and Shiva. The temple has images of Vishnu, possibly because of the rising prominence of [[Jagannath]] sect emanating from the Ganga rulers who built the [[Jagannath Temple, Puri|Jagannath Temple]] in [[Puri]] in the 12th century.\n\nLingaraja temple is maintained by the Temple Trust Board and the [[Archaeological Survey of India]] (ASI). The temple has an average of 6,000 visitors per day and receives lakhs of visitors during festivals. [[Shivaratri]] festival is the major festival celebrated in the temple and event during 2012 witnessed 200,000 visitors.  The temple compound is not open to non-Hindus, but there is a viewing platform beside the wall offering a good view of the main exteriors.  This was originally erected for a visit by [[Lord Curzon]] when [[Viceroy of India|Viceroy]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Lingaraj Temple Complex.jpg|thumb|left|Central [[vimana]] and temples in the Lingaraja Temple complex.]]\n[[File:Lingaraj temple Bhubaneswar 11005.jpg|thumb|left|Minor temples in the Lingaraja Temple complex.|alt=Image of a conical temple tower with smaller shrines around it.]]\nLingaraja, literally means the king of [[Lingam]], the iconic form of Shiva. Shiva was originally worshipped as Kirtivasa and later as Harihara and is commonly referred to as Tribhuvaneshwara (also called Bhubaneswar), the master of three worlds, namely, heaven, earth, and netherworld. His consort is called [[Bhuvaneshvari]].\n\nThe temple in its present form dates back to the last decade of the eleventh century. There is evidence that part of the temple was built during the sixth century CE as mentioned in some of the seventh century Sanskrit texts.<ref name=\"Bhubaneswar Lingaraj Temple\">{{cite web\n |url=http://www.orissatourism.gov.in/new/lingaraj.html \n |title=Bhubaneswar Lingaraj Temple \n |publisher=Tourism Development Corporation of Odisha \n |accessdate=9 July 2015 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130206132524/http://www.orissatourism.gov.in/new/lingaraj.html \n |archivedate= 6 February 2013 \n}}</ref> [[James Fergusson (architect)|Fergusson]] believes that the temple might have been initiated by Lalat Indu Keshari who reigned from 615 to 657 CE. The Assembly hall (''jagamohana''), sanctum and temple tower were built during the eleventh century, while the Hall of offering (''bhoga-mandapa'') was built during the twelfth century. The ''natamandira'' was built by the wife of Salini between 1099 and 1104 CE.<ref>{{cite book|title=History of Indian and Eastern architecture, Volume 3|last=Fergusson|first=James |url=https://books.google.com/?id=JXZAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA419&dq=Parasurameswara+Temple#v=onepage&q=Parasurameswara%20Temple&f=false|pages= 422\u2013424|publisher=Harvard University|year=1876| location  =London}}</ref> By the time the Lingaraja temple was completely constructed, the [[Jagannath]] (form of Vishnu) sect had been growing in the region, which historians believe, is evidenced by the co-existence of [[Vishnu]] and Shiva worship at the temple. The kings of Ganga dynasty were ardent followers of [[Vaishnavism]] and built the [[Jagannath Temple]] at [[Puri]] in the 12th century.<ref name=\"Upinder\">{{cite book|last=Singh|first=Upinder|title=A History of Ancient and Early Medieval India: From the Stone Age to the 12th Century|year=2008|publisher=Pearson Education India| location  =New Delhi|isbn=978-813-17-1120-0|page=622|url=https://books.google.com/?id=H3lUIIYxWkEC&pg=PR14&dq=lingaraj+temple#v=onepage&q=lingaraj%20temple&f=false}}</ref>\n\nAs per some accounts, the temple is believed to have been built by the Somavanshi king [[Jajati Keshari|Yayati I]] (1025-1040), during the 11th century CE.<ref name=\"Upinder\"/> Jajati Keshari shifted his capital from Jajpur to Bhubaneswar which was referred to as ''Ekamra Kshetra'' in the [[Brahma Purana]], an ancient scripture. One of the Somavamsi queens donated a village to the temple and the Brahmins attached to the temple received generous grants.<ref>[[#Patnaik|Patnaik 1997]], pp. 40-41</ref> An inscription from the Saka year 1094 (1172 CE) indicates gifts of gold coins to the temple by Rajaraja II.<ref>[[#Patnaik|Patnaik]] 1997, p. 57</ref> Another inscription of Narasimha I from the 11th century indicates offer of beetel leaves as ''tambula'' to the presiding deity.<ref>[[#Patnaik|Patnaik 1997]], p. 145</ref> Other stone inscriptions in the temple indicate royal grants from Chodaganga to the nearby village people.<ref>[[#Patnaik|Patnaik 1997]], p. 59</ref>\n\nK.C. Panigrahi mentions that Yayti I had no time to build the temple and it should have been initiated by his sons Ananta Kesari and Udyota Kesari (believed to be other names of Yayati II as well). The argument provided against the view is that is his weak successors could not have constructed such a magnificent structure.<ref name=Parida/>\n\nCertain anecdotal accounts maintain that the temple was commissioned by [[Shashanka]] the King of Gauda (died c. 637 CE).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mishra |first1=Sweta |title=The King Who Brought Shaivism To Odisha |url=http://www.odishabytes.com/king-brought-shaivism-odisha/ |website=Odisha Bytes |date=30 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:Lingaraj map.jpg|right|thumb|Temple plan of Lingaraja temple: from the top ''[[vimana (tower)|vimana]]'' (structure containing the sanctum), ''jagamohana'' (assembly hall), ''natamandira'' (festival hall) and ''bhoga-mandapa'' (hall of offerings)|alt=temple plan for four spires of a temple]]\n[[File:Bhuvanesvar1016.jpg|thumb|250px| lateral view of Li\u1e45gar\u0101ja temple, [[Bhubaneshwar|Bhubane\u015bvara]].]]\nThe Lingaraja temple is the largest temple in Bhubaneswar. [[James Fergusson (architect)|James Fergusson]] (1808\u201386), a noted critic and historian rated the temple as \"one of the finest examples of purely Hindu temple in India\".<ref name=\"Bhubaneswar Corporation\"/> It is enshrined within a spacious compound wall of [[laterite]] measuring {{convert|520|ft|m|abbr=on}} by {{convert|465|ft|m|abbr=on}}. The wall is {{convert|7.5|ft|m|abbr=on}} thick and surmounted by a plain slant coping. Alongside the inner face of the boundary wall, there is a terrace to protect the compound wall against outside aggression.<ref name=\"Ramesh Prasad Mohapatra 1986 Page 69\">[[Ramesh Prasad Mohapatra]] (1986) Page 69. ''Archaeology in Orissa Vol I''. B. R. Publishers, Delhi {{ISBN|81-7018-346-4}}</ref> The tower is {{convert|45.11|m|ft|abbr=on}} high and the complex has 150 smaller shrines in its spacious courtyard. Each inch of the {{convert|55|m|ft|abbr=on}} tall tower is sculpted.<ref name=\"Bhubaneswar Corporation\"/><ref name=Parida>[[#Parida|Parida 1999]], pp. 105-8</ref> The door in the gate of the entrance porch is made of sandalwood.<ref>[[#Patnaik|Patnaik 1997]], p. 43</ref>\n\nThe Lingaraja temple faces east and is built of [[sandstone]] and [[laterite]]. The main entrance is located in the east, while there are small entrances in the north and south. The temple is built in the ''[[Deula]]'' style that has four components namely, ''[[vimana]]'' (structure containing the sanctum), ''[[jagamohana]]'' (assembly hall), ''natamandira'' (festival hall) and ''bhoga-mandapa'' (hall of offerings), with all four in axial alignment with descending height.<ref name=Parida/><ref name=\"Ali\">{{cite book|title=World Heritage Monuments|url=https://books.google.com/?id=54XBlIF9LFgC&pg=PA197&dq=lingaraja+temple|first1=\u02bbAl\u012b |last1=J\u0101v\u012bd|first2=Tabassum |last2=Javeed|pages=197\u2013201|publisher=Algora Publishing|year=2008|isbn=9780875864846}}</ref> The dance hall was associated with the raising prominence of the [[devadasi system]] that existed during the time.<ref name=\"Bhubaneswar Lingaraj Temple\"/> The various units from the Hall of offering to the tower of the sanctum increase in height.\n\nThe ''bhogamandapa'' (Hall of offering) measures {{convert|42|ft|m|abbr=on}}*{{convert|42|ft|m|abbr=on}} from the inside,  {{convert|56.25|ft|m|abbr=on}}*{{convert|56.25|ft|m|abbr=on}} from the outside and has four doors in each of the sides. The exterior walls of the hall has decorative sculptures of men and beast. The hall has a pyramidal roof made of up several horizontal layers arranged in sets of two with intervening platform. It bears an inverted bell and a ''[[kalasa]]'' in the top.<ref name=\"Ali\"/><ref name=\"size\">[[#A.|A. 1950]], p.73</ref><ref name=\"encyclo\">{{Cite book |last=Brockman |first=Norbert C. |authorlink= |title= Encyclopedia of Sacred Places |year=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO, LLC | location  =California |isbn=978-1-59884-655-3|pages=212\u2013213}}</ref> The ''natamandira'' (festival hall) measures {{convert|38|ft|m|abbr=on}}*{{convert|38|ft|m|abbr=on}} from the inside,  {{convert|50|ft|m|abbr=on}}*{{convert|50|ft|m|abbr=on}} from the outside, has one main entrance and two side entrances. The side walls of the hall has decortive sculptures displaying women and couples. It has a flat roof sloping in stages. There are thick pylons inside the hall.<ref name=\"Ali\"/><ref name=\"size\"/><ref>{{cite book|title=Dance and Architecture: Body, Form, Space and Transformation|first=Smritilekha|last=Nayak|url=https://books.google.com/?id=LuZUMh9uCpQC&pg=PT19&dq=lingaraj+temple#v=onepage&q=isbn&f=false|isbn=9780549965183|year=2008|page=10}}</ref>\nThe ''jagamohana'' (assembly hall) measures {{convert|35|ft|m|abbr=on}}*{{convert|30|ft|m|abbr=on}} from the inside,  {{convert|55|ft|m|abbr=on}}*{{convert|50|ft|m|abbr=on}} from the outside, entrances from south and north and has a {{convert|30|m|ft}} tall roof. The hall has a pyramidal roof made of up several horizontal layers arranged in sets of two with intervening platform as in the Hall of offering. The facade to the entrances are decorated with perforated windows with lion sitting on hind legs. The inverted bell above second unit is adorned by ''kalasa'' and lions.<ref name=\"Ali\"/><ref name=\"size\"/> The ''rekha deula'' has a {{convert|60|m|ft|abbr=on}} tall pyramidal tower over the sanctum and measures {{convert|22|ft|m|abbr=on}}*{{convert|22|ft|m|abbr=on}} from the inside,  {{convert|52|ft|m|abbr=on}}*{{convert|52|ft|m|abbr=on}} from the outside over the sanctum. It is covered with decorative design and seated lion projecting from the walls. The sanctum is square in shape from the inside. The tower walls are sculpted with female figures in different poses.<ref name=\"Ali\"/><ref name=\"size\"/>\n\nThe temple has a vast courtyard mired with hundreds of small shrines.<ref name=Parida/>\n\n==Religious significance==\n[[File:Lingaraj Temple, Bhubaneswar (4) - Oct 2010.jpg|thumb|The flag of the temple fixed to a Pinaka bow|alt=sculpture of lion projecting from the main spire of the temple]]\nBhubaneswar is called the Ekamra Kshetra as the deity of Lingaraja was originally under a mango tree (Ekamra). ''Ekamra Purana'', a Sanskrit treatise of the 13th century mentions that the presiding deity was not seen as [[lingam]] (an aniconic form of Shiva) during the [[Satya Yuga|Satya]] and [[Treta yuga]]s and only during the [[Dvapara Yuga|Dwapara]] and [[Kali]] yugas, it emerged as a lingam. The lingam in the temple is a natural unshaped stone that rests on a Sakti. Such a lingam is called Krutibasa or [[Swayambhu]] and is found in 64 places in different parts of India. With the advent of the Ganga dynasty in the early 12th century, who had Vaishnavaite orientation, a new movement started resulting in the synthesis of [[Saivism]] and [[Vaishnavism]]. The Ekamra was associated with Vaishanavite gods [[Krishna]] and [[Balaram]] during the period.<ref name=\"ekamra\">{{cite journal|title=Lingaraj Worship in Ekamra Kshetra |date=April 2011 |volume=LXVII |issue=9 |pages=61\u201362 |url=http://orissa.gov.in/e-magazine/Orissareview/2011/Apr/engpdf/april.pdf |journal=The Orissa Review |publisher=Government of Orissa |accessdate=29 December 2012 |last=Panda |first=Dr.Saroj Kumar |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203033726/http://orissa.gov.in/e-magazine/Orissareview/2011/Apr/engpdf/april.pdf |archivedate= 3 December 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIt is attributed the raising prominence of Jagannath sect that became predominant during the construction of the temple. The Gangas remodelled the temple and introduced certain Vaishnavite elements like images of Vaishnava Dwarapalas namely Jaya and Prachanda, [[Jagannatha]], Lakshmi Narayan and [[Garuda]] were installed. Tulsi leaves, which are favoured by [[Vishnu]], was used along with Bela leaves for the worship of Lingaraja. Lingaraja thus came to be known as Harihara, a combination of Shiva and Vishnu. The flag of the temple was fixed to a Pinaka bow instead of trident usually found in Shiva temples. The temple priests also changed the mark in their forehead from horizontal to a \"U\" sign with a dotted middle line. The Gangas also introduced certain fairs like Swing festival, Sun worship and mock quarrel between priests after chariot festival, similar to the practises in Jagannath Temple in Puri. The influence of the Ganga dynasty has led to cosmopolitan culture, that has reduced the status of Lingaraja temple as a distinct Saivite shrine.<ref name=\"Bhubaneswar Lingaraj Temple\"/><ref name=\"ekamra\"/>\n\n==Festival and worship practises==\nAs per Hindu legend, an underground river originating from the Lingaraja temple fills the [[Bindusagar Tank]] (meaning ocean drop) and the water is believed to heal physical and spiritual illness. The water from the tank is thus treated sacred and pilgrims take a holy dip during festive occasions.<ref name=\"encyclo\"/><ref name=\"Seymour\">{{cite book|title=Women, Family, and Child Care in India: A World in Transition|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ClkaIF3KzLIC&pg=PA18&dq=lingaraj+temple#v=onepage&q=lingaraj%20temple&f=false|page=18|last=Seymour|first=Susan C.|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1999|isbn=0-521-59127-9}}</ref>\nThe central deity of the temple, Lingaraja, is worshipped both as Shiva and Vishnu. The harmony between the two sects of Hinduism, Shaivism, and Vaishanvism, is seen in this temple where the deity is worshipped as [[Harihara]], a combined form of Vishnu and Shiva.<ref name=\"Bhubaneswar Lingaraj Temple\"/>\n\n[[File:Rukuna Rath 1.jpg|thumb|left|Rukuna Ratha yatra is an annual Ratha yatra of Lingaraja|200px|alt=festival cart of the temple with image of the festival deity]]\n[[Shivaratri]] is the main festival celebrated annually in [[Phalgun]] month when thousands of devotees visit the temple.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thousands throng Lingaraj temple on Mahashivratri|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1961148191.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140610055814/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1961148191.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 June 2014|accessdate=29 December 2012|newspaper=Hindutan times, Delhi{{Subscription required|via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}|date=12 February 2010}}</ref> Apart from a full day of fasting, ''bel'' leaves are offered to Lingaraja on this auspicious day. The main celebrations take place at night when devotees pray all night long. The devout usually break their fast after the ''Mahadipa'' (a huge lamp) is lit on the spire of the temple. This festival commemorates Lingaraja having slain a demon. Thousands of ''bol bom'' pilgrims carry water from river [[Mahanadi]] and walk all the way to the temple during the month of Shravana every year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thousands congregate at Lingaraj temple |url=http://www.hindu.com/2008/07/28/stories/2008072856470300.htm |date=28 July 2008|accessdate=13 January 2012|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> Sunian day is observed from royal times in the month of Bhandra, a day when temple servants, peasants and other holders of temple lands offer loyalty and tribute to Lingaraja.<ref name=\"Misra1213\"/>\nCandan Yatra (Sandalwood ceremony) is a 22-day festival celebrated in the temple when servants of the temple disport themselves in a specially made barge in Bindusagar tank. The deities and servants of the temples are anointed with sandalwood paste to protect from heat. Dances, communal feasts, and merrymaking are arranged by the people associated with the temple.<ref name=\"E.J.\"/>\n\nEvery year the chariot festival ([[Ratha-Yatra]]) of Lingaraja is celebrated on ''Ashokashtami''. The deity is taken in a chariot to [[Rameshwar Deula]] temple. Thousands of devotees follow and pull brightly decorated chariots containing the idols of Lingaraja and his sister Rukmani.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hindus participate in Lingaraja's chariot procession in Bhubaneshwar|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1244699681.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140610060106/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1244699681.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 June 2014|accessdate=15 September 2012|newspaper=Hindustan Times, Delhi{{Subscription required|via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}|date=27 March 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe Lingaraja temple is active in worship practises, unlike the other ancient temples of Bhubaneshwar which are not active worship centres. Non Hindus are not allowed inside the temple, but it can be viewed from the viewing platform located outside the temple. The viewing platform and the back of the temple can be reached via a lineway located to the right of the main entrance of the temple.<ref name=\"Bhubaneswar Corporation\">{{cite web\n |url         = http://bmc.gov.in/TouristAtcton.asp?lnk=2&PL=5\n |title       = Bhubaneswar tourist attractions\n |publisher   = Bhubaneswar Municipal Corporation\n |accessdate  = 12 September 2006\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110810003759/http://bmc.gov.in/TouristAtcton.asp?lnk=2&PL=5\n |archivedate = 10 August 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Bhubaneswar Lingaraj Temple\"/><ref name=\"encyclo\"/> Sanctity of the temple is maitained by disallowing dogs, unbathed visitors, mensturating women and families that encountered birth or death in the preceding 12 days.<ref>{{cite book|title=Culture and Depression: Studies in the Anthropology and Cross-Cultural Psychiatry of Affect and Disorder |url=https://books.google.com/?id=qSXap1Us-CAC&pg=PA205&dq=lingaraj+temple#v=onepage&q=lingaraj%20temple&f=false|first=Arthur |last=Kleinman|page=206|author2=Byron Good |publisher=University of California Press|year=1985| location  =London|isbn=0-520-05493-8}}</ref> In case of a foreign trespass, the temple follows a purification ritual and dumping of ''prasad'' (food offering) in a well.<ref name=\"admin1\">{{cite news|title=Russian enters Lingaraj temple|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-01-24/bhubaneswar/30658776_1_hindu-nri-boy-ryszard-ankur-ahuja-russian-tourist|date=24 January 2012|accessdate=13 January 2012|newspaper=The Times of India}}</ref><ref name=\"admin2\">{{cite news|title=Russian held for entering Lingaraj temple |url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/state-editions/bhubaneswar/37695-russian-held-for-entering-lingaraj-temple.html|date=25 January 2012|accessdate=13 January 2012|newspaper=The Daily Pioneer}}</ref>\n\n==Religious practices==\n[[File:Lingaraj Temple bbsr10.jpg|thumb|The main spire of the temple|alt=main conical spire of the temple]]\nThe image of Lingaraja is abluted with water (called ''mahasnana'') several times a day and decorated with flowers, sandal paste and cloth. [[Conium|Hemlock]] or hemlock flowers which are generally offered in other Shiva temples is not allowed in the Lingaraja temple. [[Aegle marmelos|Bilva]] leaves (Aegle marmelos) and [[tulasi]] (Ocimum sanctum) are used in daily worship. Offerings of cooked rice, curries and sweets are displayed in the ''bhogamandapa'' (hall of offering) and the divinity is invoked to accept them amidst scores of chanting of Sanskrit texts. Coconut, ripe plantains and [[Lia (food)|kora-khai]] are generally offered to Lingaraja by the pilgrims. [[Bhang]] beverage is offered to Lingaraja by some devotees especially on the day of [[Pana Sankranti]] (Odia new year).\n\nThe Lingaraja temple is open from 6 a.m. to about 9 p.m. and is intermittently closed during ''bhoga'' (food offering) to the deity. During early morning, lamps in the cella are lit to awaken Lingaraja from his sleep, ablution is performed, followed by adoration and ''[[arati]]'' (waving of light). The temple is closed at about 12 noon until about 3.30 p.m.  A ceremony is known as  ''Mahasnana'' (ablution)  is performed once the doors are closed, followed by pouring of ''[[Panchamrita]]'' (a mixture of milk, curdled milk, clarified butter, honey, and ghee) upon the deity for purification. At about 1:00&nbsp;p.m., a ripe plantain is divided into two, one half is offered to Sun god and the other half to Dwarapala (the guarding deities in the doorway).  Between 1 p.m. and 1:30&nbsp;p.m.  the food offering called ''Ballabha Bhoga'' (breakfast containing curdled milk, curd, and vegetables) is offered to the deity. The consecrated food is carried to the temple of Parvati and placed before her as an offering, a practice commonly observed by the orthodox Hindu housewives. At about 2 p.m., the ''Sakala Dhupa'' (morning's offering of food) takes place. After the food is offered to Lingaraja, the offerings are carried to the temple of Parvati to serve her.  An offering called ''Bhanda Dhupa'' is carried out at 3:30&nbsp;p.m. at the hall of the offering. This food is later offered by the inmates to the pilgrims as ''[[prasad|Mahaprasada]]''.\n\nA light refreshment known as ''Ballabha Dhupa'' is offered to the deity at around 4:30&nbsp;p.m. At around 5:00&nbsp;p.m., ''Dwipahar Dhupa'' (mid-day meal) is offered. At around 7 p.m., another offering called ''Palia Badu'' is placed before the deity. ''Sandhya arati'' (waving of lights in the evening) is performed during that time. Another light meal called ''Sahana Dhupa'' is offered at around 8:30&nbsp;p.m. After the meals, the ceremony of waving light (''arati'') is performed before the deity. At 9.30 p.m., the last service of the day, ''Bada Singara'' (the great decoration) is performed when the deity is decorated with flowers and ornaments after which a light food offering is made. A wooden palanquin is laid in the room, incense is lighted, drinking water is served and prepared betel is placed. Panchabaktra Mahadeva comes to the palanquin and returns to his own abode after the ''arati'' is performed. This is a bronze image of Mahadeva having five faces and Parvati in his lap. Each of these ceremonies is accompanied by ritual observances and recitations of mantras (Sanskrit texts) specified for each occasion.<ref name=\"district\">{{cite web|title=Lord Lingaraja|url=http://khordha.nic.in/lingaraj/lingaraj.htm|publisher=Khordha district administration|accessdate=12 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120502041651/http://khordha.nic.in/lingaraj/lingaraj.htm|archive-date=2 May 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Temple staff and administration==\n\nKing Jajati Keshari, believed to be the founder of the Lingaraja temple, deputed [[Brahmins]] who had migrated to south India as temple priests over the local Brahmins on account of their increased knowledge of Shaivism, due to increasing invasions from Muslim invaders. The focus was to enhance the temple practises from tribal rites to Sanskritic. While the exact number of castes involved in the ''nijogas'' (practises) is not known, Brahmins, tribal worshippers and inmates from [[Untouchable caste]]s are believed to be part of the setup.  Bose (1958) identified 41 services with the involvement of 22 separate castes and Mahaptra (1978) identified 30 services. It is understood from the records that kings and temple managers of different times introduced or discontinued certain services, fairs, offerings, and caste-centred core services during their regime.<ref name=\"Misra1213\">[[#Misra|Misra 1978]], pp. 12-13</ref> As of 2012, the temple practised 36 different services (''nijogas'').<ref name=\"nijogas\">{{cite news|title=Lingaraj servitors threaten strike|url=http://newindianexpress.com/states/odisha/article1295930.ece |date=9 August 2010|accessdate=12 October 2012|newspaper=The Hindustan Times}}</ref>\n\nIn modern times, the Lingaraja temple priests are from three communities, namely Pujapanda Nijog, Brahman Nijog and Badu Nijog.<ref>{{cite news|title=Warring priests bring Lingaraj temple rituals to a halt|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-newdelhi/warring-priests-bring-lingaraj-temple-rituals-to-a-halt/article560448.ece?css=print |date=9 August 2010|accessdate=13 January 2012|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> The Badu are non-Brahmin servant groups, whose origin is not ascertained due to unavailability of authentic records, while they are described as Vadu in chapter 62 of the ''Ekamrapurana''. The caste group of Badu is called Niyoga, which elects the officers every year during the Sandalwood festival. Every Badu undergoes three distinct rites, namely, ear-piercing, marriage, and god-touching. Historically, the Badus performed five different temple duties - Paliabadu and Pharaka, which were considered important and Pochha, Pahada and Khataseja, which were considered inferior. From 1962, only Paliabadu and Pharaka practises are followed and the others are discontinued. The Badus also carry out ablution and dressing of the images of Siddhaganesh and Gopalini.<ref name=\"E.J.\">[[#E.J.|E.J. 1973]], pp.96-107</ref>\nThe temple is maintained by the Temple Trust Board and the [[Archaeological Survey of India]] (ASI). The temple is guarded by security personnel deputed by the Police Commissioner of Bhubaneswar and security guards appointed by the temple administration.<ref name=\"admin1\"/><ref name=\"admin2\"/> The temple has an average of 6,000 visitors every day and receives lakhs of visitors during festivals.<ref name=\"ASI\">{{cite news|title=Cracks in Lingaraj on ASI team radar temple|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-12-30/bhubaneswar/36063333_1_lingaraj-temple-cracks-dadhinauti|date=30 December 2012|accessdate=13 January 2012|newspaper=The Times of India}}</ref> The Shivaratri festival during 2012 witnessed 200,000 visitors.<ref>{{cite news|title=Over two lakh devotees throng Lingaraj temple temple|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-otherstates/article2915014.ece?css=print|date=21 February 2012|accessdate=13 January 2012|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> As of 2011, the annual income of Lingaraja temple from [[hundi]]s (donation boxes) is around {{INR}}1.2&nbsp;million per annum. Another {{INR}}4&nbsp;million is collected annually from other sources like rents from shops, cycle stands and agriculture lands. Starting 2011, the temple charges an amount for six types of religious worship (special [[pujas]]) carried out by the devotees.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lingaraj to charge fee for spl pujas|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-09-06/bhubaneswar/30118028_1_fee-collection-abani-pattnaik-shrine-authorities|date=6 October 2011|accessdate=13 January 2012|newspaper=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=packed>\nFile:Lingaraj Temple, Bhubaneswar (3) - Oct 2010.jpg|A sculpted griffin or \"udagajasingha\" on the main temple spire.\nFile:Bindu Sagar Lord Lingaraj Temple Bhubaneswar Odisha.jpg|Image of Bindusagar pond with Lingaraja temple in the background.\nFile:Marigold at lingaraj temple.jpg|Varieties of Marigold for offering to Lingaraja during Shivaratri at Bhubaneswar.\nFile:Birds eye view of Lingaraj Temple during Deepa Dana.jpg|Birds eye view of Lingaraj Temple during Deepa Dana February 2020.\nFile:Lingaraj Temple complex at dusk during Shivratri 2020.jpg|thumb|Lingaraj Temple complex at dusk during Shivratri 2020.\n</gallery>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Refbegin|3}}\n* {{cite book|title=Designs from Orissan Temples|last1=A.|first1=Goswami|year=1950|url=http://asi.nic.in/asi_books/14834.pdf|publisher=Thacker's Press and Directories, Limited|location=Calcutta and London|ref=A.|access-date=2 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304200215/http://asi.nic.in/asi_books/14834.pdf|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}\n* {{cite book|title=Contributions to Asian Studies: 1973|last1=E.J.|first1=Brills |url=https://books.google.com/?id=8QYVAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA103&dq=lingaraj+temple#v=onepage&q=lingaraj%20temple&f=false|ref=E.J.|publisher=Brill Academic Publishers|year=1973| location  =Netherlands|isbn=9789004035386}}\n*{{cite book|title=Early Temples of Orissa|last=Parida|first=A.N.|publisher=Commonwealth Publishers| location  =New Delhi|isbn=81-7169-519-1|ref=Parida|year=1999|edition=1st}}\n* {{cite book|title=Community, Self and Identity|last1=Misra|first1=Bhabagrahi |last2=Preston|first2=James |url=https://books.google.com/?id=jgDTCVW51WkC&pg=PA12&dq=lingaraj+temple#v=onepage&q=lingaraj%20temple&f=false|publisher=Mounton Publishers|year=1978| location  =Great Britain|isbn=90-279-7650-3|ref=Misra}}\n* {{cite book|title=Economic History of Orissa|last1=Patnaik|first1=Nihar Ranjan|year=1997 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=1AA9W9_4Z9gC&pg=PA43&dq=lingaraj+temple#v=onepage&q=lingaraj%20temple&f=false|publisher=Indus Publishing Company| location  =New Delhi|isbn=81-7387-075-6|ref=Patnaik}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Lingaraj Temple}}\n\n<nowiki/>{{Shaivism}}\n{{Shiva temples}} \n{{Hindu temples in Odisha}}\n\n[[Category:Ancient Indian culture]]\n[[Category:11th-century Hindu temples]]\n[[Category:Hindu temples in Bhubaneswar]]\n[[Category:Shiva temples in Odisha]]\n[[Category:Vishnu temples]]\n[[Category:Archaeological monuments in Odisha]]\n[[Category:Sandstone buildings in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Hindu temple in Bhubaneswar, Odisha}}\n{{Redirect|Lingaraj|activist|Lingaraj Azad}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox Hindu temple\n| name               = Lingaraja Temple\n| native_name =\n| native_name_lang = or\n| image              = Beauty of LingrajTemple.jpg\n| caption            =\n| map_type        = <!-- India Odisha -->\n| map_caption        = Location in Odisha\n| coordinates        = {{coord|20|14|18|N|85|50|01|E|type:landmark_region:IN|display=inline,title}}\n| country            = India\n| state     = [[Odisha]]\n| district           = [[Khurda]]\n| locale             = Lingaraja Temple Road, Old Town, [[Bhubaneshwar]]\n| elevation_m        =\n| tradition = Saivism\n| deity      = [[Shiva]] As [[Shiva|Lingaraja]], [[Shiva|Adi Shiva]], [[Shiva|Adidev]] ([[Shiva|Maheswara]], [[Shiva|Tribhuvaneshwara]], [[Shiva|Bhubaneswar]]), \n[[Vishnu]] As [[Vishnu|Adi Narayana]], ([[Harihara]]) <br />\n[[Bhuvaneshvari]] Form of [[Parvati]] (consort)\n| festivals= [[Shivaratri]]\n| architecture       = [[Kalinga Architecture]]\n| temple_quantity  =\n| monument_quantity=\n| inscriptions       =\n| year_completed         = 11th century CE\n| creator            = Jajati Keshari\n| website            = http://www.lordlingaraj.org.in/\n}}\n{{Saivism}}\n'''Lingaraja Temple''' is a [[Hindu temple]] dedicated to [[Shiva]] and is one of the oldest temples in [[Bhubaneswar]], the capital of the Indian state of [[Odisha]]. The temple is the most prominent landmark of Bhubaneswar city and one of the major tourist attractions of the state.<ref name=\"Bhubaneswar Corporation\"/><ref name=\"ASI\"/><ref>{{cite book|title=India through the ages|url=https://archive.org/details/indiathroughages00mada|last=Gopal|first=Madan|year= 1990| page= [https://archive.org/details/indiathroughages00mada/page/175 175]|editor=K.S. Gautam|publisher=Publication Division, Ministry of Information and Broadcasting, Government of India}}</ref>\n\nThe Lingaraja temple is the largest temple in Bhubaneswar. The central tower of the temple is {{cvt|180|ft|m}} tall. The temple represents the quintessence of the [[Kalinga architecture]] and culminating the medieval stages of the architectural tradition at Bhubaneswar.<ref name=\"Ramesh Prasad Mohapatra 1986 Page 69\"/> The temple is believed to be built by the kings from the [[Somava\u1e43\u015b\u012b dynasty|Somavamsi dynasty]], with later additions from the [[Eastern Ganga dynasty|Ganga]] rulers. The temple is built in the ''[[Deula]]'' style that has four components namely, ''[[vimana]]'' (structure containing the sanctum), ''[[jagamohana]]'' (assembly hall), ''natamandira'' (festival hall) and ''bhoga-mandapa'' (hall of offerings), each increasing in the height to its predecessor. The temple complex has 50 other shrines and is enclosed by a large compound wall.\n\nBhubaneswar is called the Ekamra Kshetra as the deity of Lingaraja was originally under a mango tree (Ekamra) as noted in ''Ekamra Purana'', a 13th-century [[Sanskrit]] treatise. The temple is active in worship practises, unlike most other temples in Bhubaneswar and Shiva is worshipped as [[Harihara]], a combined form of Vishnu and Shiva. The temple has images of Vishnu, possibly because of the rising prominence of [[Jagannath]] sect emanating from the Ganga rulers who built the [[Jagannath Temple, Puri|Jagannath Temple]] in [[Puri]] in the 12th century.\n\nLingaraja temple is maintained by the Temple Trust Board and the [[Archaeological Survey of India]] (ASI). The temple has an average of 6,000 visitors per day and receives lakhs of visitors during festivals. [[Shivaratri]] festival is the major festival celebrated in the temple and event during 2012 witnessed 200,000 visitors.  The temple compound is not open to non-Hindus, but there is a viewing platform beside the wall offering a good view of the main exteriors.  This was originally erected for a visit by [[Lord Curzon]] when [[Viceroy of India|Viceroy]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Lingaraj Temple Complex.jpg|thumb|left|Central [[vimana]] and temples in the Lingaraja Temple complex.]]\n[[File:Lingaraj temple Bhubaneswar 11005.jpg|thumb|left|Minor temples in the Lingaraja Temple complex.|alt=Image of a conical temple tower with smaller shrines around it.]]\nLingaraja, literally means the king of [[Lingam]], the iconic form of Shiva. Shiva was originally worshipped as Kirtivasa and later as Harihara and is commonly referred to as Tribhuvaneshwara (also called Bhubaneswar), the master of three worlds, namely, heaven, earth, and netherworld. His consort is called [[Bhuvaneshvari]].\n\nThe temple in its present form dates back to the last decade of the eleventh century. There is evidence that part of the temple was built during the sixth century CE as mentioned in some of the seventh century Sanskrit texts.<ref name=\"Bhubaneswar Lingaraj Temple\">{{cite web\n |url=http://www.orissatourism.gov.in/new/lingaraj.html \n |title=Bhubaneswar Lingaraj Temple \n |publisher=Tourism Development Corporation of Odisha \n |accessdate=9 July 2015 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130206132524/http://www.orissatourism.gov.in/new/lingaraj.html \n |archivedate= 6 February 2013 \n}}</ref> [[James Fergusson (architect)|Fergusson]] believes that the temple might have been initiated by Lalat Indu Keshari who reigned from 615 to 657 CE. The Assembly hall (''jagamohana''), sanctum and temple tower were built during the eleventh century, while the Hall of offering (''bhoga-mandapa'') was built during the twelfth century. The ''natamandira'' was built by the wife of Salini between 1099 and 1104 CE.<ref>{{cite book|title=History of Indian and Eastern architecture, Volume 3|last=Fergusson|first=James |url=https://books.google.com/?id=JXZAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA419&dq=Parasurameswara+Temple#v=onepage&q=Parasurameswara%20Temple&f=false|pages= 422\u2013424|publisher=Harvard University|year=1876| location  =London}}</ref> By the time the Lingaraja temple was completely constructed, the [[Jagannath]] (form of Vishnu) sect had been growing in the region, which historians believe, is evidenced by the co-existence of [[Vishnu]] and Shiva worship at the temple. The kings of Ganga dynasty were ardent followers of [[Vaishnavism]] and built the [[Jagannath Temple]] at [[Puri]] in the 12th century.<ref name=\"Upinder\">{{cite book|last=Singh|first=Upinder|title=A History of Ancient and Early Medieval India: From the Stone Age to the 12th Century|year=2008|publisher=Pearson Education India| location  =New Delhi|isbn=978-813-17-1120-0|page=622|url=https://books.google.com/?id=H3lUIIYxWkEC&pg=PR14&dq=lingaraj+temple#v=onepage&q=lingaraj%20temple&f=false}}</ref>\n\nAs per some accounts, the temple is believed to have been built by the Somavanshi king [[Jajati Keshari|Yayati I]] (1025-1040), during the 11th century CE.<ref name=\"Upinder\"/> Jajati Keshari shifted his capital from Jajpur to Bhubaneswar which was referred to as ''Ekamra Kshetra'' in the [[Brahma Purana]], an ancient scripture. One of the Somavamsi queens donated a village to the temple and the Brahmins attached to the temple received generous grants.<ref>[[#Patnaik|Patnaik 1997]], pp. 40-41</ref> An inscription from the Saka year 1094 (1172 CE) indicates gifts of gold coins to the temple by Rajaraja II.<ref>[[#Patnaik|Patnaik]] 1997, p. 57</ref> Another inscription of Narasimha I from the 11th century indicates offer of beetel leaves as ''tambula'' to the presiding deity.<ref>[[#Patnaik|Patnaik 1997]], p. 145</ref> Other stone inscriptions in the temple indicate royal grants from Chodaganga to the nearby village people.<ref>[[#Patnaik|Patnaik 1997]], p. 59</ref>\n\nK.C. Panigrahi mentions that Yayti I had no time to build the temple and it should have been initiated by his sons Ananta Kesari and Udyota Kesari (believed to be other names of Yayati II as well). The argument provided against the view is that is his weak successors could not have constructed such a magnificent structure.<ref name=Parida/>\n\nCertain anecdotal accounts maintain that the temple was commissioned by [[Shashanka]] the King of Gauda (died c. 637 CE).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mishra |first1=Sweta |title=The King Who Brought Shaivism To Odisha |url=http://www.odishabytes.com/king-brought-shaivism-odisha/ |website=Odisha Bytes |date=30 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:Lingaraj map.jpg|right|thumb|Temple plan of Lingaraja temple: from the top ''[[vimana (tower)|vimana]]'' (structure containing the sanctum), ''jagamohana'' (assembly hall), ''natamandira'' (festival hall) and ''bhoga-mandapa'' (hall of offerings)|alt=temple plan for four spires of a temple]]\n[[File:Bhuvanesvar1016.jpg|thumb|250px| lateral view of Li\u1e45gar\u0101ja temple, [[Bhubaneshwar|Bhubane\u015bvara]].]]\nThe Lingaraja temple is the largest temple in Bhubaneswar. [[James Fergusson (architect)|James Fergusson]] (1808\u201386), a noted critic and historian rated the temple as \"one of the finest examples of purely Hindu temple in India\".<ref name=\"Bhubaneswar Corporation\"/> It is enshrined within a spacious compound wall of [[laterite]] measuring {{convert|520|ft|m|abbr=on}} by {{convert|465|ft|m|abbr=on}}. The wall is {{convert|7.5|ft|m|abbr=on}} thick and surmounted by a plain slant coping. Alongside the inner face of the boundary wall, there is a terrace to protect the compound wall against outside aggression.<ref name=\"Ramesh Prasad Mohapatra 1986 Page 69\">[[Ramesh Prasad Mohapatra]] (1986) Page 69. ''Archaeology in Orissa Vol I''. B. R. Publishers, Delhi {{ISBN|81-7018-346-4}}</ref> The tower is {{convert|45.11|m|ft|abbr=on}} high and the complex has 150 smaller shrines in its spacious courtyard. Each inch of the {{convert|55|m|ft|abbr=on}} tall tower is sculpted.<ref name=\"Bhubaneswar Corporation\"/><ref name=Parida>[[#Parida|Parida 1999]], pp. 105-8</ref> The door in the gate of the entrance porch is made of sandalwood.<ref>[[#Patnaik|Patnaik 1997]], p. 43</ref>\n\nThe Lingaraja temple faces east and is built of [[sandstone]] and [[laterite]]. The main entrance is located in the east, while there are small entrances in the north and south. The temple is built in the ''[[Deula]]'' style that has four components namely, ''[[vimana]]'' (structure containing the sanctum), ''[[jagamohana]]'' (assembly hall), ''natamandira'' (festival hall) and ''bhoga-mandapa'' (hall of offerings), with all four in axial alignment with descending height.<ref name=Parida/><ref name=\"Ali\">{{cite book|title=World Heritage Monuments|url=https://books.google.com/?id=54XBlIF9LFgC&pg=PA197&dq=lingaraja+temple|first1=\u02bbAl\u012b |last1=J\u0101v\u012bd|first2=Tabassum |last2=Javeed|pages=197\u2013201|publisher=Algora Publishing|year=2008|isbn=9780875864846}}</ref> The dance hall was associated with the raising prominence of the [[devadasi system]] that existed during the time.<ref name=\"Bhubaneswar Lingaraj Temple\"/> The various units from the Hall of offering to the tower of the sanctum increase in height.\n\nThe ''bhogamandapa'' (Hall of offering) measures {{convert|42|ft|m|abbr=on}}*{{convert|42|ft|m|abbr=on}} from the inside,  {{convert|56.25|ft|m|abbr=on}}*{{convert|56.25|ft|m|abbr=on}} from the outside and has four doors in each of the sides. The exterior walls of the hall has decorative sculptures of men and beast. The hall has a pyramidal roof made of up several horizontal layers arranged in sets of two with intervening platform. It bears an inverted bell and a ''[[kalasa]]'' in the top.<ref name=\"Ali\"/><ref name=\"size\">[[#A.|A. 1950]], p.73</ref><ref name=\"encyclo\">{{Cite book |last=Brockman |first=Norbert C. |authorlink= |title= Encyclopedia of Sacred Places |year=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO, LLC | location  =California |isbn=978-1-59884-655-3|pages=212\u2013213}}</ref> The ''natamandira'' (festival hall) measures {{convert|38|ft|m|abbr=on}}*{{convert|38|ft|m|abbr=on}} from the inside,  {{convert|50|ft|m|abbr=on}}*{{convert|50|ft|m|abbr=on}} from the outside, has one main entrance and two side entrances. The side walls of the hall has decortive sculptures displaying women and couples. It has a flat roof sloping in stages. There are thick pylons inside the hall.<ref name=\"Ali\"/><ref name=\"size\"/><ref>{{cite book|title=Dance and Architecture: Body, Form, Space and Transformation|first=Smritilekha|last=Nayak|url=https://books.google.com/?id=LuZUMh9uCpQC&pg=PT19&dq=lingaraj+temple#v=onepage&q=isbn&f=false|isbn=9780549965183|year=2008|page=10}}</ref>\nThe ''jagamohana'' (assembly hall) measures {{convert|35|ft|m|abbr=on}}*{{convert|30|ft|m|abbr=on}} from the inside,  {{convert|55|ft|m|abbr=on}}*{{convert|50|ft|m|abbr=on}} from the outside, entrances from south and north and has a {{convert|30|m|ft}} tall roof. The hall has a pyramidal roof made of up several horizontal layers arranged in sets of two with intervening platform as in the Hall of offering. The facade to the entrances are decorated with perforated windows with lion sitting on hind legs. The inverted bell above second unit is adorned by ''kalasa'' and lions.<ref name=\"Ali\"/><ref name=\"size\"/> The ''rekha deula'' has a {{convert|60|m|ft|abbr=on}} tall pyramidal tower over the sanctum and measures {{convert|22|ft|m|abbr=on}}*{{convert|22|ft|m|abbr=on}} from the inside,  {{convert|52|ft|m|abbr=on}}*{{convert|52|ft|m|abbr=on}} from the outside over the sanctum. It is covered with decorative design and seated lion projecting from the walls. The sanctum is square in shape from the inside. The tower walls are sculpted with female figures in different poses.<ref name=\"Ali\"/><ref name=\"size\"/>\n\nThe temple has a vast courtyard mired with hundreds of small shrines.<ref name=Parida/>\n\n==Religious significance==\n[[File:Lingaraj Temple, Bhubaneswar (4) - Oct 2010.jpg|thumb|The flag of the temple fixed to a Pinaka bow|alt=sculpture of lion projecting from the main spire of the temple]]\nBhubaneswar is called the Ekamra Kshetra as the deity of Lingaraja was originally under a mango tree (Ekamra). ''Ekamra Purana'', a Sanskrit treatise of the 13th century mentions that the presiding deity was not seen as [[lingam]] (an aniconic form of Shiva) during the [[Satya Yuga|Satya]] and [[Treta yuga]]s and only during the [[Dvapara Yuga|Dwapara]] and [[Kali]] yugas, it emerged as a lingam. The lingam in the temple is a natural unshaped stone that rests on a Sakti. Such a lingam is called Krutibasa or [[Swayambhu]] and is found in 64 places in different parts of India. With the advent of the Ganga dynasty in the early 12th century, who had Vaishnavaite orientation, a new movement started resulting in the synthesis of [[Saivism]] and [[Vaishnavism]]. The Ekamra was associated with Vaishanavite gods [[Krishna]] and [[Balaram]] during the period.<ref name=\"ekamra\">{{cite journal|title=Lingaraj Worship in Ekamra Kshetra |date=April 2011 |volume=LXVII |issue=9 |pages=61\u201362 |url=http://orissa.gov.in/e-magazine/Orissareview/2011/Apr/engpdf/april.pdf |journal=The Orissa Review |publisher=Government of Orissa |accessdate=29 December 2012 |last=Panda |first=Dr.Saroj Kumar |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203033726/http://orissa.gov.in/e-magazine/Orissareview/2011/Apr/engpdf/april.pdf |archivedate= 3 December 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIt is attributed the raising prominence of Jagannath sect that became predominant during the construction of the temple. The Gangas remodelled the temple and introduced certain Vaishnavite elements like images of Vaishnava Dwarapalas namely Jaya and Prachanda, [[Jagannatha]], Lakshmi Narayan and [[Garuda]] were installed. Tulsi leaves, which are favoured by [[Vishnu]], was used along with Bela leaves for the worship of Lingaraja. Lingaraja thus came to be known as Harihara, a combination of Shiva and Vishnu. The flag of the temple was fixed to a Pinaka bow instead of trident usually found in Shiva temples. The temple priests also changed the mark in their forehead from horizontal to a \"U\" sign with a dotted middle line. The Gangas also introduced certain fairs like Swing festival, Sun worship and mock quarrel between priests after chariot festival, similar to the practises in Jagannath Temple in Puri. The influence of the Ganga dynasty has led to cosmopolitan culture, that has reduced the status of Lingaraja temple as a distinct Saivite shrine.<ref name=\"Bhubaneswar Lingaraj Temple\"/><ref name=\"ekamra\"/>\n\n==Festival and worship practises==\nAs per Hindu legend, an underground river originating from the Lingaraja temple fills the [[Bindusagar Tank]] (meaning ocean drop) and the water is believed to heal physical and spiritual illness. The water from the tank is thus treated sacred and pilgrims take a holy dip during festive occasions.<ref name=\"encyclo\"/><ref name=\"Seymour\">{{cite book|title=Women, Family, and Child Care in India: A World in Transition|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ClkaIF3KzLIC&pg=PA18&dq=lingaraj+temple#v=onepage&q=lingaraj%20temple&f=false|page=18|last=Seymour|first=Susan C.|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1999|isbn=0-521-59127-9}}</ref>\nThe central deity of the temple, Lingaraja, is worshipped both as Shiva and Vishnu. The harmony between the two sects of Hinduism, Shaivism, and Vaishanvism, is seen in this temple where the deity is worshipped as [[Harihara]], a combined form of Vishnu and Shiva.<ref name=\"Bhubaneswar Lingaraj Temple\"/>\n\n[[File:Rukuna Rath 1.jpg|thumb|left|Rukuna Ratha yatra is an annual Ratha yatra of Lingaraja|200px|alt=festival cart of the temple with image of the festival deity]]\n[[Shivaratri]] is the main festival celebrated annually in [[Phalgun]] month when thousands of devotees visit the temple.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thousands throng Lingaraj temple on Mahashivratri|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1961148191.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140610055814/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1961148191.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 June 2014|accessdate=29 December 2012|newspaper=Hindutan times, Delhi{{Subscription required|via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}|date=12 February 2010}}</ref> Apart from a full day of fasting, ''bel'' leaves are offered to Lingaraja on this auspicious day. The main celebrations take place at night when devotees pray all night long. The devout usually break their fast after the ''Mahadipa'' (a huge lamp) is lit on the spire of the temple. This festival commemorates Lingaraja having slain a demon. Thousands of ''bol bom'' pilgrims carry water from river [[Mahanadi]] and walk all the way to the temple during the month of Shravana every year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thousands congregate at Lingaraj temple |url=http://www.hindu.com/2008/07/28/stories/2008072856470300.htm |date=28 July 2008|accessdate=13 January 2012|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> Sunian day is observed from royal times in the month of Bhandra, a day when temple servants, peasants and other holders of temple lands offer loyalty and tribute to Lingaraja.<ref name=\"Misra1213\"/>\nCandan Yatra (Sandalwood ceremony) is a 22-day festival celebrated in the temple when servants of the temple disport themselves in a specially made barge in Bindusagar tank. The deities and servants of the temples are anointed with sandalwood paste to protect from heat. Dances, communal feasts, and merrymaking are arranged by the people associated with the temple.<ref name=\"E.J.\"/>\n\nEvery year the chariot festival ([[Ratha-Yatra]]) of Lingaraja is celebrated on ''Ashokashtami''. The deity is taken in a chariot to [[Rameshwar Deula]] temple. Thousands of devotees follow and pull brightly decorated chariots containing the idols of Lingaraja and his sister Rukmani.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hindus participate in Lingaraja's chariot procession in Bhubaneshwar|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1244699681.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140610060106/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1244699681.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 June 2014|accessdate=15 September 2012|newspaper=Hindustan Times, Delhi{{Subscription required|via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}|date=27 March 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe Lingaraja temple is active in worship practises, unlike the other ancient temples of Bhubaneshwar which are not active worship centres. Non Hindus are not allowed inside the temple, but it can be viewed from the viewing platform located outside the temple. The viewing platform and the back of the temple can be reached via a lineway located to the right of the main entrance of the temple.<ref name=\"Bhubaneswar Corporation\">{{cite web\n |url         = http://bmc.gov.in/TouristAtcton.asp?lnk=2&PL=5\n |title       = Bhubaneswar tourist attractions\n |publisher   = Bhubaneswar Municipal Corporation\n |accessdate  = 12 September 2006\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110810003759/http://bmc.gov.in/TouristAtcton.asp?lnk=2&PL=5\n |archivedate = 10 August 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Bhubaneswar Lingaraj Temple\"/><ref name=\"encyclo\"/> Sanctity of the temple is maitained by disallowing dogs, unbathed visitors, mensturating women and families that encountered birth or death in the preceding 12 days.<ref>{{cite book|title=Culture and Depression: Studies in the Anthropology and Cross-Cultural Psychiatry of Affect and Disorder |url=https://books.google.com/?id=qSXap1Us-CAC&pg=PA205&dq=lingaraj+temple#v=onepage&q=lingaraj%20temple&f=false|first=Arthur |last=Kleinman|page=206|author2=Byron Good |publisher=University of California Press|year=1985| location  =London|isbn=0-520-05493-8}}</ref> In case of a foreign trespass, the temple follows a purification ritual and dumping of ''prasad'' (food offering) in a well.<ref name=\"admin1\">{{cite news|title=Russian enters Lingaraj temple|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-01-24/bhubaneswar/30658776_1_hindu-nri-boy-ryszard-ankur-ahuja-russian-tourist|date=24 January 2012|accessdate=13 January 2012|newspaper=The Times of India}}</ref><ref name=\"admin2\">{{cite news|title=Russian held for entering Lingaraj temple |url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/state-editions/bhubaneswar/37695-russian-held-for-entering-lingaraj-temple.html|date=25 January 2012|accessdate=13 January 2012|newspaper=The Daily Pioneer}}</ref>\n\n==Religious practices==\n[[File:Lingaraj Temple bbsr10.jpg|thumb|The main spire of the temple|alt=main conical spire of the temple]]\nThe image of Lingaraja is abluted with water (called ''mahasnana'') several times a day and decorated with flowers, sandal paste and cloth. [[Conium|Hemlock]] or hemlock flowers which are generally offered in other Shiva temples is not allowed in the Lingaraja temple. [[Aegle marmelos|Bilva]] leaves (Aegle marmelos) and [[tulasi]] (Ocimum sanctum) are used in daily worship. Offerings of cooked rice, curries and sweets are displayed in the ''bhogamandapa'' (hall of offering) and the divinity is invoked to accept them amidst scores of chanting of Sanskrit texts. Coconut, ripe plantains and [[Lia (food)|kora-khai]] are generally offered to Lingaraja by the pilgrims. [[Bhang]] beverage is offered to Lingaraja by some devotees especially on the day of [[Pana Sankranti]] (Odia new year).\n\nThe Lingaraja temple is open from 6 a.m. to about 9 p.m. and is intermittently closed during ''bhoga'' (food offering) to the deity. During early morning, lamps in the cella are lit to awaken Lingaraja from his sleep, ablution is performed, followed by adoration and ''[[arati]]'' (waving of light). The temple is closed at about 12 noon until about 3.30 p.m.  A ceremony is known as  ''Mahasnana'' (ablution)  is performed once the doors are closed, followed by pouring of ''[[Panchamrita]]'' (a mixture of milk, curdled milk, clarified butter, honey, and ghee) upon the deity for purification. At about 1:00&nbsp;p.m., a ripe plantain is divided into two, one half is offered to Sun god and the other half to Dwarapala (the guarding deities in the doorway).  Between 1 p.m. and 1:30&nbsp;p.m.  the food offering called ''Ballabha Bhoga'' (breakfast containing curdled milk, curd, and vegetables) is offered to the deity. The consecrated food is carried to the temple of Parvati and placed before her as an offering, a practice commonly observed by the orthodox Hindu housewives. At about 2 p.m., the ''Sakala Dhupa'' (morning's offering of food) takes place. After the food is offered to Lingaraja, the offerings are carried to the temple of Parvati to serve her.  An offering called ''Bhanda Dhupa'' is carried out at 3:30&nbsp;p.m. at the hall of the offering. This food is later offered by the inmates to the pilgrims as ''[[prasad|Mahaprasada]]''.\n\nA light refreshment known as ''Ballabha Dhupa'' is offered to the deity at around 4:30&nbsp;p.m. At around 5:00&nbsp;p.m., ''Dwipahar Dhupa'' (mid-day meal) is offered. At around 7 p.m., another offering called ''Palia Badu'' is placed before the deity. ''Sandhya arati'' (waving of lights in the evening) is performed during that time. Another light meal called ''Sahana Dhupa'' is offered at around 8:30&nbsp;p.m. After the meals, the ceremony of waving light (''arati'') is performed before the deity. At 9.30 p.m., the last service of the day, ''Bada Singara'' (the great decoration) is performed when the deity is decorated with flowers and ornaments after which a light food offering is made. A wooden palanquin is laid in the room, incense is lighted, drinking water is served and prepared betel is placed. Panchabaktra Mahadeva comes to the palanquin and returns to his own abode after the ''arati'' is performed. This is a bronze image of Mahadeva having five faces and Parvati in his lap. Each of these ceremonies is accompanied by ritual observances and recitations of mantras (Sanskrit texts) specified for each occasion.<ref name=\"district\">{{cite web|title=Lord Lingaraja|url=http://khordha.nic.in/lingaraj/lingaraj.htm|publisher=Khordha district administration|accessdate=12 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120502041651/http://khordha.nic.in/lingaraj/lingaraj.htm|archive-date=2 May 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Temple staff and administration==\n\nKing Jajati Keshari, believed to be the founder of the Lingaraja temple, deputed [[Brahmins]] who had migrated to south India as temple priests over the local Brahmins on account of their increased knowledge of Shaivism, due to increasing invasions from Muslim invaders. The focus was to enhance the temple practises from tribal rites to Sanskritic. While the exact number of castes involved in the ''nijogas'' (practises) is not known, Brahmins, tribal worshippers and inmates from [[Untouchable caste]]s are believed to be part of the setup.  Bose (1958) identified 41 services with the involvement of 22 separate castes and Mahaptra (1978) identified 30 services. It is understood from the records that kings and temple managers of different times introduced or discontinued certain services, fairs, offerings, and caste-centred core services during their regime.<ref name=\"Misra1213\">[[#Misra|Misra 1978]], pp. 12-13</ref> As of 2012, the temple practised 36 different services (''nijogas'').<ref name=\"nijogas\">{{cite news|title=Lingaraj servitors threaten strike|url=http://newindianexpress.com/states/odisha/article1295930.ece |date=9 August 2010|accessdate=12 October 2012|newspaper=The Hindustan Times}}</ref>\n\nIn modern times, the Lingaraja temple priests are from three communities, namely Pujapanda Nijog, Brahman Nijog and Badu Nijog.<ref>{{cite news|title=Warring priests bring Lingaraj temple rituals to a halt|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-newdelhi/warring-priests-bring-lingaraj-temple-rituals-to-a-halt/article560448.ece?css=print |date=9 August 2010|accessdate=13 January 2012|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> The Badu are non-Brahmin servant groups, whose origin is not ascertained due to unavailability of authentic records, while they are described as Vadu in chapter 62 of the ''Ekamrapurana''. The caste group of Badu is called Niyoga, which elects the officers every year during the Sandalwood festival. Every Badu undergoes three distinct rites, namely, ear-piercing, marriage, and god-touching. Historically, the Badus performed five different temple duties - Paliabadu and Pharaka, which were considered important and Pochha, Pahada and Khataseja, which were considered inferior. From 1962, only Paliabadu and Pharaka practises are followed and the others are discontinued. The Badus also carry out ablution and dressing of the images of Siddhaganesh and Gopalini.<ref name=\"E.J.\">[[#E.J.|E.J. 1973]], pp.96-107</ref>\nThe temple is maintained by the Temple Trust Board and the [[Archaeological Survey of India]] (ASI). The temple is guarded by security personnel deputed by the Police Commissioner of Bhubaneswar and security guards appointed by the temple administration.<ref name=\"admin1\"/><ref name=\"admin2\"/> The temple has an average of 6,000 visitors every day and receives lakhs of visitors during festivals.<ref name=\"ASI\">{{cite news|title=Cracks in Lingaraj on ASI team radar temple|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-12-30/bhubaneswar/36063333_1_lingaraj-temple-cracks-dadhinauti|date=30 December 2012|accessdate=13 January 2012|newspaper=The Times of India}}</ref> The Shivaratri festival during 2012 witnessed 200,000 visitors.<ref>{{cite news|title=Over two lakh devotees throng Lingaraj temple temple|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-otherstates/article2915014.ece?css=print|date=21 February 2012|accessdate=13 January 2012|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> As of 2011, the annual income of Lingaraja temple from [[hundi]]s (donation boxes) is around {{INR}}1.2&nbsp;million per annum. Another {{INR}}4&nbsp;million is collected annually from other sources like rents from shops, cycle stands and agriculture lands. Starting 2011, the temple charges an amount for six types of religious worship (special [[pujas]]) carried out by the devotees.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lingaraj to charge fee for spl pujas|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-09-06/bhubaneswar/30118028_1_fee-collection-abani-pattnaik-shrine-authorities|date=6 October 2011|accessdate=13 January 2012|newspaper=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=packed>\nFile:Lingaraj Temple, Bhubaneswar (3) - Oct 2010.jpg|A sculpted griffin or \"udagajasingha\" on the main temple spire.\nFile:Bindu Sagar Lord Lingaraj Temple Bhubaneswar Odisha.jpg|Image of Bindusagar pond with Lingaraja temple in the background.\nFile:Marigold at lingaraj temple.jpg|Varieties of Marigold for offering to Lingaraja during Shivaratri at Bhubaneswar.\nFile:Birds eye view of Lingaraj Temple during Deepa Dana.jpg|Birds eye view of Lingaraj Temple during Deepa Dana Februry 2020.\nFile:Lingaraj Temple complex at dusk during Shivratri 2020.jpg|thumb|Lingaraj Temple complex at dusk during Shivratri 2020.\n</gallery>\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Refbegin|3}}\n* {{cite book|title=Designs from Orissan Temples|last1=A.|first1=Goswami|year=1950|url=http://asi.nic.in/asi_books/14834.pdf|publisher=Thacker's Press and Directories, Limited|location=Calcutta and London|ref=A.|access-date=2 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304200215/http://asi.nic.in/asi_books/14834.pdf|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}\n* {{cite book|title=Contributions to Asian Studies: 1973|last1=E.J.|first1=Brills |url=https://books.google.com/?id=8QYVAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA103&dq=lingaraj+temple#v=onepage&q=lingaraj%20temple&f=false|ref=E.J.|publisher=Brill Academic Publishers|year=1973| location  =Netherlands|isbn=9789004035386}}\n*{{cite book|title=Early Temples of Orissa|last=Parida|first=A.N.|publisher=Commonwealth Publishers| location  =New Delhi|isbn=81-7169-519-1|ref=Parida|year=1999|edition=1st}}\n* {{cite book|title=Community, Self and Identity|last1=Misra|first1=Bhabagrahi |last2=Preston|first2=James |url=https://books.google.com/?id=jgDTCVW51WkC&pg=PA12&dq=lingaraj+temple#v=onepage&q=lingaraj%20temple&f=false|publisher=Mounton Publishers|year=1978| location  =Great Britain|isbn=90-279-7650-3|ref=Misra}}\n* {{cite book|title=Economic History of Orissa|last1=Patnaik|first1=Nihar Ranjan|year=1997 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=1AA9W9_4Z9gC&pg=PA43&dq=lingaraj+temple#v=onepage&q=lingaraj%20temple&f=false|publisher=Indus Publishing Company| location  =New Delhi|isbn=81-7387-075-6|ref=Patnaik}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Lingaraj Temple}}\n\n\n<nowiki/>{{Shaivism}}\n{{Shiva temples}} \n{{Hindu temples in Odisha}}\n\n[[Category:Ancient Indian culture]]\n[[Category:11th-century Hindu temples]]\n[[Category:Hindu temples in Bhubaneswar]]\n[[Category:Shiva temples in Odisha]]\n[[Category:Vishnu temples]]\n[[Category:Archaeological monuments in Odisha]]\n[[Category:Sandstone buildings in India]]\n", "name_user": "Lakun.patra", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: Februry \u2192 February", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lingaraja_Temple"}
{"title_page": "The Wool Road (New South Wales)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date = November 2019}}\n'''The Wool Road''' (also later known as 'The Old Wool Road') was a [[Historic roads|historic road]] of New South Wales, Australia, that ran from [[Nerriga, New South Wales|Nerriga]] to what is now [[Vincentia, New South Wales|Vincentia]] on [[Jervis Bay]]. It was constructed privately in 1841, using convict labour. Its purpose was to provide a shorter route to a seaport for wool grown at [[Braidwood, New South Wales|Braidwood]] and beyond.\n\nThe historical significance of The Wool Road is that it was the first road, capable of being used by wheeled vehicles, linking the inland area around [[Braidwood, New South Wales|Braidwood]] to the [[South Coast (New South Wales)|South Coast]]. The road led to the foundation of the privately-owned port town of South Huskisson (called [[Vincentia, New South Wales|Vincentia]] since 1952) and the adjacent 'government townshIp' of [[Huskisson, New South Wales|Huskisson]].\n\nThe Wool Road's route made its use difficult and the port on Jervis Bay was not a success. In 1856, the original road was realigned and extended to [[Terara]] (near [[Nowra, New South Wales|Nowra]]) instead of Jervis Bay, becoming the Braidwood Road. The old route through the coastal escarpment to Jervis Bay fell into disuse for many years.\n\nMuch of the original route of The Wool Road remains in use today but some parts are accessible only to four-wheel drive traffic. Only a part of the original route that is currently in use is known as The Wool Road or The Old Wool Road today\u2014the section from the Princes Highway to Vincentia. The remainder of the original route still in use today is made up of a significant part of the Braidwood Road (MR92), Wandean Road, and a short section of the Princes Highway.[[File:Wandean Gap - Bottom of First Sideling of 1841 Wool Road in February 2019.jpg|thumb|256x256px|Wandean Gap - The bottom of the first of three steep sidelings on  Wandean Road (1841 Wool Road) that take it from the plateau of the Pigeon House Range to the ridge-line sloping toward the coast. (February 2019)]]\n\n== Historical context ==\n[[File:Wandandian tool-sharpening grooves near Wool Road route outside Vincentia (April 2019).jpg|thumb|282x282px|Tool-sharpening groves made by  Wandandian people, in sandstone rock nearby the route of The Wool Road, outside Vincentia, N.S.W. (April 2019)]]\nThe land between Nerriga and Jervis Bay is part of the country of the [[Wandandian people]], a group of the [[Yuin]]. The [[Wandandian people]],<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://ro.uow.edu.au/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1007&context=uowbooks|title=Illawarra and South Coast Aborigines 1770-1850|last=Organ|first=Michael|date=1990|publisher=Aboriginal Education Unit Wollongong University|page=401|isbn=086418-112-4}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Aboriginal Tribes of Australia|last=Tindale|first=N.B.|publisher=University of California Press|year=1974|isbn=|location=Berkeley|pages=}}</ref> spoke Dharamba,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collection.aiatsis.gov.au/austlang/language/s56|title=S56: Dharamba|website=collection.aiatsis.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref> which was probably the northernmost dialect of the [[Dhurga language]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/dharawaldhurgala0000eade/page/4|title=The Dharawal and Dhurga languages of the New South Wales South Coast|last=Eades|first=Diana|date=1976|publisher=Australian Institute of Aboriginal Studies|isbn=0855750510|location=Canberra|pages=[https://archive.org/details/dharawaldhurgala0000eade/page/4 4, 5, 6]|oclc=2948202}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collection.aiatsis.gov.au/austlang/language/s53|title=S53: Dhurga|website=collection.aiatsis.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2019-02-27}}</ref> Traditionally, the [[Wandandian people]] used paths, from the Pigeon House Range through the area now known as [[Wandandian, New South Wales|Wandandian]], to reach the fishing grounds of [[St Georges Basin (New South Wales)|St George's Basin]] and the inland hunting areas of the tablelands. In the 1830s and 1840s, the Wandandian people still lived on their traditional lands.\n\nThe land also lay within the [[St Vincent County|County of St. Vincent]], one of the [[Nineteen Counties]] in which white settlement was permitted by the colonial government of New South Wales. In the late 1820s and 1830s colonial settlement had spread to the vicinity of [[Lake George (New South Wales)|Lake George]], [[Braidwood, New South Wales|Braidwood]], [[Yass, New South Wales|Yass]], the Limestone Plains (now [[Canberra]]), and beyond to the [[Monaro (New South Wales)|Monaro district]]. The country settled was well-suited for the production of wool, for which there was a booming export market, but lay far from the existing port of Sydney. Transporting the [[wool bale]]s using the cumbersome [[Bullocky|bullock drays]] of the time involved a long and arduous journey from Braidwood\u2014taking around three weeks at the bullock's slow pace and with their need to stop for rest, feeding and watering\u2014via [[Bungonia, New South Wales|Bungonia]] and [[Goulburn, New South Wales|Goulburn]] to Sydney. The owner of [[Government House, Canberra#History of the site|Yarralumla]], [[Terence Aubrey Murray|Terence Murray]], further away at the Limestone Plains, complained that, in wet weather, the drays could take as long as three months to reach Sydney.<ref>{{Citation|last=Wilson|first=Gwendoline|title=Murray, Sir Terence Aubrey (1810\u20131873)|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/murray-sir-terence-aubrey-2498|work=Australian Dictionary of Biography|publisher=National Centre of Biography, Australian National University|access-date=2018-12-11}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1830s, a bridle-track known as the Corn Trail was made, from [[Clyde Mountain]] to the coastal [[Buckenbowra River|Buckenbowra Valley]], but it was steep and only usable by pack horses. Transport of wool in [[Wool bale|bales]] required a road that could be used by bullock drays.\n\nJervis Bay, a large sheltered bay that was suitable as a deepwater port lay far closer than Sydney but there was no road from Braidwood toward the coast beyond Nerriga. From 1831, there were sea-going auxiliary steamships\u2014such as the ''[[Sophia Jane]]''\u2014operating in New South Wales but steam powered railways were not in place before the mid-1850s.\n\nAlthough transportation of [[Convicts in Australia|convicts]] to New South Wales had ceased in 1840, it was still a penal colony. Convicts were a workforce that could be put to work on roadmaking.\n\n== Route ==\n[[File:Tianjara Creek looking north from Tianjara falls.jpg|thumb|209x209px|The valley of Tianjara Creek, looking north from Tianjara Falls. The  Wool Road passed south of the top of the falls to avoid this valley and the nearby valley of the Clyde River.]]\nThe endpoints of The Wool Road were the village of [[Nerriga, New South Wales|Nerriga]]\u2014by 1841 already connected to Braidwood by a rudimentary road\u2014and the newly created port of South Huskisson (later known as 'the old township' and today known as [[Vincentia, New South Wales|Vincentia]]) on Jervis Bay. The significant geographical obstacles to be overcome were crossing the [[Endrick River]] near Nerriga, climbing to a plateau in the northern part of the Pigeon House Range, then avoiding the steep valleys and gorges cut into that plateau by tributaries of the [[Shoalhaven River|Shoalhaven]] and [[Clyde River (New South Wales)|Clyde]] rivers, and subsequently descending from the plateau to the coastal plain to reach Jervis Bay.\n\nAfter fording the Endrick River, The Wool Road broadly followed the direction of the modern-day Braidwood Road (MR92), from Nerriga to near the Boolijah Peak, a point east of [[Sassafras, New South Wales|Sassafras]]. The current Braidwood Road alignment is the result of an upgrade in 1856. The original 1841 road's exact route was different in some places, most significantly where it climbs the Pigeon House Range at Bulee Mountain near Nerriga. The 1841 road traversed the ridge to the north of Bulee Mountain and went through the man-made Bulee Gap,<ref name=\":5\" />  whereas the 1856 alignment and the current road pass to the south of Bulee Mountain[[File:Sussex Inlet from Jerrawangala lookout.jpg|thumb|View from Jerrawangala lookout atop the coastal escarpment approx. 500m south of Wandean Gap. St George's Basin is visible in the centre and beyond it,  to its left, in the far distance, is Jervis Bay.|202x202px]]Following the line of the modern Braidwood Road, the road crested the Pigeon House Range, at a location known as Billy's Hill. It then passed over the narrow part of the plateau not cut by the impassable gorges of Ettrema Creek (and Bainbrig Creek It continued past [[Sassafras, New South Wales|Sassafras]] and the Tianjara Falls, through another narrow part of the plateau, between the impassable valleys of [[Tianjara|Tianjara Creek]] and the most upstream parts of the [[Clyde River (New South Wales)|Clyde River]].\n\nFrom near the Boolijah Peak, The Wool Road diverged from the current route of the Braidwood Road and followed the route of modern-day Wandean Road, through the steep Wandean Gap.<ref name=\":5\" /> (historically also known as the Jerrawangala Gap<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article229236583|title=JERVIS BAY. THE WOOL ROAD|last=|first=|date=1914-04-20|work=Sun (Sydney, NSW : 1910 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-08|pages=12}}</ref>), then following ridgelines of tributaries of Wandandian Creek, to [[Wandandian, New South Wales|Wandandian]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|title=Sassafras : the story of the Post Town at Sassafras Mountain on the old Wool Road in the County of St. Vincent|last=Charles.|first=Snedden, Robert|date=1996|publisher=R C Snedden|isbn=0646259822|location=Duffy, A.C.T.|pages=22|oclc=38411506}}</ref> In this section, the road's elevation dropped by approximately 2,500 feet in 10 miles<ref name=\":3\" /> (760m in 16&nbsp;km), as it descended the coastal escarpment, via the locality of [[Jerrawangala]] and [[Wandandian, New South Wales|Wandandian]]. Most of this part of the route is now only accessible to four-wheel drive traffic.<ref name=\":0\">{{Citation|last=Bob James|title=Wandean Rd Wandanian|date=2016-01-20|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5eDu7z9OweM|access-date=2018-11-23}} A video showing travel from Braidwood Road to Wandandian. The Wandean Gap section of the road is shown between 3:50 and 4:40.</ref>\n\nFrom Wandandian, The Wool Road followed the route of a previous foot track\u2014already in existence by 1841<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=http://stgeorgesbasin.info/level3/larmer%20report.html|title=Larmer's Survey of the Wool Road|website=stgeorgesbasin.info|access-date=2018-12-18}}</ref> and probably of Aboriginal origin\u2014to Jervis Bay. Its route followed the approximate line of the existing [[Princes Highway]] for a short distance (skirting north of Wandandian Creek).,<ref name=\":5\" /> then broadly followed the direction of the modern road still known as 'The Wool Road', from the modern-day Princes Highway near [[Basin View]], via [[St Georges Basin, New South Wales|St George's Basin]] to [[Vincentia, New South Wales|Vincentia]]. At St. George's Basin, the 1841 route followed the road now known as 'The Old Wool Road' where it deviates from a section of the modern-day The Wool Road that was constructed around 1929.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article213797940|title=A TRIP TO ST. GEORGE'S BASIN.|date=1929-06-28|work=Nowra Leader (NSW : 1909 - 1939)|access-date=2018-12-13|pages=8}}</ref> The Wool Road ended at a port on [[Jervis Bay]] that is now Vincentia.\n\n== History ==\n=== Finding the Route ===\nIn 1831, Robert Futter of [[Bungonia, New South Wales|Bungonia]] and George Galbraith of Nerriga formed an expedition to find a path from Nerriga to Jervis Bay. The others making up the expedition were William Ryrie, [[James Holman]]\u2014who was known as the 'Blind Traveller'\u2014and two Aboriginal guides<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|title=Sassafras : the story of the Post Town at Sassafras Mountain on the old Wool Road in the County of St. Vincent|last=Charles.|first=Snedden, Robert|date=1996|publisher=R C Snedden|isbn=0646259822|location=Duffy, A.C.T.|pages=19|oclc=38411506}}</ref> whose names are not known.\n\nHolman later recounted\u2014in his book  ''\u2018A Voyage Round The World: Including Travels In Africa, Asia, Australia, America Etc. From 1827 - 1832' ,'' published in 1834-1835 \u2014that the route they had taken from Yerock Flat (west of Sassafras Mountain) to the coast was taken against the advice of the Aboriginal guides, who had strongly suggested following the range further to the north. Holman later recognised that had they done so they could have found a far easier route for a road to Jervis Bay<ref name=\":6\" /> (such as that of the longer but less steep Turpentine Road). However, the explorers had passed through rugged and difficult country and, having reached Jervis Bay via what was apparently the shortest route, did not search for any longer but easier route.\n\nIn 1839, the owner of [[Yarralumla, Australian Capital Territory#Settlement|Yarralumla]], [[Terence Aubrey Murray]], also explored a route between Nerriga and Jervis Bay, which may have been similar to that followed by the Futter expedition.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Nerriga on the wool road|last=Pam.|first=Radowitz|date=1990|publisher=Nerriga Historical Museum|others=Nerriga Historical Museum.|isbn=0646006010|location=[Nerriga, N.S.W.]|pages=19|oclc=27515653}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article31726503|title=Country News.|date=1839-09-27|work=Australasian Chronicle (Sydney, NSW : 1839 - 1843)|access-date=2019-01-09|pages=4}}</ref>\n\n=== Proponents ===\nAfter at first failing to obtain government funding for such a road in 1839,<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article31724219|title=The Colonist.|date=1839-12-18|work=Colonist (Sydney, NSW : 1835 - 1840)|access-date=2019-01-13|pages=2}}</ref> landholders from around Braidwood and Nerriga decided to build their own road from Nerriga to Jervis Bay. The principal advocates and financial backers for the new road were Colonel John McKenzie of Nerriga and [[Thomas Braidwood Wilson|Dr. Thomas Braidwood Wilson]] of Braidwood. Wealthy and influential colonists [[Terence Aubrey Murray]], [[Alexander Berry]], [[Robert Campbell (1769\u20131846)|Robert Campbell]], [[Thomas Walker (philanthropist)|Thomas Walker]] and [[James Macarthur (politician)|James Macarthur]] were also supporters of the new road.<ref name=\":16\" />\n\n[[Edward Deas Thomson|Edward Deas Thompson]]\u2014at the time the [[Chief Secretary of New South Wales|Colonial Secretary of New South Wales]]\u2014stood to benefit from the construction of the road. He owned 2,560 acres of otherwise useless land on the western shore of Jervis Bay south of Moona Moona Creek,<ref name=\":13\" /> where an east-facing point\u2014now known as Plantation Point\u2014provided shelter from the south and a safe port\u2014the 'Inner Harbour'\u2014and a port township could be situated.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n=== Survey ===\nThe route of the new road was surveyed by a government surveyor, James Larmer, who delivered his final report on the route in August 1840. Larmer advocated the same basic route followed by the Futter and Murray expeditions and\u2014apparently in ignorance\u2014dismissed any route descending to the coast further north than his surveyed line. His report reads, ''\"In conclusion I beg to add that on so great an extent of Road less obstructions and difficulties in the formation could not be met on any other line of Road of the same extent in the Colony\u2014and from enquiries I have made both from whites and Aboriginals and from my own observations I am fully convinced that it would be impossible to discover a more practicable line than the one now Surveyed. On the North it is a bold and continuous range but totally unfit for Drays to pass down to the Coast\u2014and on the South numerous deep rocky gullies that are impassable.\"''<ref name=\":12\" />\n\n=== Construction ===\nSeventy convicts were assigned to Nerriga landowner Colonel John McKenzie, under the command of [[John Coghill (Australian politician)|Captain John Coghill]], in February 1841, and work commenced.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite book|title=Sassafras : the story of the Post Town at Sassafras Mountain on the old Wool Road in the County of St. Vincent|last=Charles.|first=Snedden, Robert|date=1996|publisher=R C Snedden|isbn=0646259822|location=Duffy, A.C.T.|pages=21, 22|oclc=38411506}}</ref>  In June 1841, another fourteen men, to work on the road, arrived at the new port of South Huskisson aboard the steamer ''Tamar''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12869734|title=DEPARTURE.|date=1841-06-21|work=Sydney Herald (NSW : 1831 - 1842)|access-date=2019-01-12|pages=2}}</ref> The Bulee Gap was created by blasting away a narrow neck of sandstone rock to bring the road onto the plateau of the Pigeon House Range. Blasting was also needed to create a pass for the descent through the Wandean Gap. The Wool Road covered a distance of approximately 37 miles (60&nbsp;km) and it was built at an estimated cost of \u00a3997.<ref name=\":1\" /> As the road neared completion, the road gang became a nuisance at the Jervis Bay end of the road; a report stated that, ''\"Scenes of debauchery and violence are of daily occurrence, there being no magistrate or constable to control them.\"''<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article31732606|title=Court of Quarter Sessions.|date=1841-08-17|work=Australasian Chronicle (Sydney, NSW : 1839 - 1843)|access-date=2019-02-27|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nThe road from Nerriga to the coast was completed in October 1841.<ref name=\":14\" />  In 1842, the existing road linking Nerriga to Braidwood was substantially upgraded, also using convict labour assigned to Colonel John Mackenzie.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rms.nsw.gov.au/documents/projects/south-coast/charleyong-bridge/charleyong-bridge-ref-appendix-f.pdf|title=Appendix F - Statement of Heritage Impact CHARLEYONG BRIDGE REPLACEMENT|last=ngh environmental|date=25 July 2017|pages=8, 9}}</ref> By late 1842 there was a road capable of taking wheeled traffic from Braidwood and beyond to Jervis Bay.\n\n=== Heyday ===\nThe first cargo of wool from Nerriga was carried over The Wool Road and loaded at South Huskisson in late 1841. At first, the drays were taken to the beach and the wool bales were carried out on small boats to a waiting ship<ref name=\":4\" />  but, after a company was formed to do so\u2014in March 1842 <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12874445|title=Advertising|date=1842-03-30|work=Sydney Herald (NSW : 1831 - 1842)|access-date=2019-01-16|pages=1}}</ref>\u2014a wharf was built<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12425035|title=JERVIS BAY.|date=1842-12-08|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-08|pages=3}}</ref> during late 1842.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12421643|title=MECHANICS' SCHOOL OF ARTS.|date=1842-09-16|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2019-01-16|pages=2}}</ref> The auxiliary steamship ''[[Sophia Jane]]'' made her first trip to the port of South Huskisson in June 1841<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article228246600|title=Shipping Intelligence.|date=1841-06-23|work=Free Press and Commercial Journal (Sydney, NSW : 1841)|access-date=2019-01-09|pages=2}}</ref> and provided a monthly<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12876234|title=Advertising|date=1842-07-19|work=Sydney Herald (NSW : 1831 - 1842)|access-date=2019-01-16|pages=1}}</ref> and at times twice monthly service between the port and Sydney.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://jervisbaymaritimemuseum.blogspot.com/2014/08/steamer-for-jervis-bay-sophia-jane.html|title=Lady Denman Museum: Steamer for Jervis Bay \u2013 the Sophia Jane.|last=Museum|first=Jervis Bay Maritime|date=2014-08-05|website=Lady Denman Museum|access-date=2018-12-08}}</ref> The barque ''Cygnet'' visited the port in December 1842 to load a cargo of wool for London.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12417944|title=COASTERS OUTWARDS.|date=1842-12-14|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-09|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nThe town of South Huskisson<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-229901982|title=Sketch of the township of South Huskisson [cartographic material].|website=nla.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2018-12-08}}</ref> grew around the port, located on land granted in 1830 to [[Edward Deas Thomson|Edward Deas Thompson]].<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article2216540|title=Classified Advertising|date=1834-07-05|work=Sydney Gazette and New South Wales Advertiser (NSW : 1803 - 1842)|access-date=2018-12-18|pages=4}}</ref> A wool store capable of storing 2,000 [[Wool bale|bales of wool]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12872568|title=Advertising|date=1841-12-01|work=Sydney Herald (NSW : 1831 - 1842)|access-date=2019-01-16|pages=1}}</ref> and an inn were built. At least 200 building allotments in the private township were sold<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article229241439|title=JERVIS BAY. CITY OF THE PAST.|last=|first=|date=1914-04-06|work=Sun (Sydney, NSW : 1910 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-08|pages=6}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article32189562|title=SOUTH HUSKISSON\u2014JERVIS BAY.|date=1841-06-18|work=Sydney Monitor and Commercial Advertiser (NSW : 1838 - 1841)|access-date=2019-01-16|pages=3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article2555128|title=Classified Advertising|date=1841-11-27|work=Sydney Gazette and New South Wales Advertiser (NSW : 1803 - 1842)|access-date=2018-12-08|pages=3}}</ref> during 1841, at high prices<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article36851732|title=No title|date=1841-06-22|work=Australian (Sydney, NSW : 1824 - 1848)|access-date=2019-01-12|pages=2}}</ref> on an assumption of the success of the road and port, and in anticipation of large future capital gains.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article2553637|title=Classified Advertising|date=1841-06-17|work=Sydney Gazette and New South Wales Advertiser (NSW : 1803 - 1842)|access-date=2019-01-12|pages=1}}</ref> The total of the prices of the 100 allotments sold in June 1841 was \u00a33,519.<ref name=\":19\" />\n\nA 'government township' was also surveyed to the north of Moona Moona Creek, which became [[Huskisson, New South Wales|Huskisson]].<ref name=\":9\" /> Allotments were sold in Huskisson in February 1843.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12413758|title=SALE OF TOWN ALLOTMENTS.|date=1843-01-18|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2019-02-26|pages=4}}</ref> Five villages were planned, as stops for bullock teams along The Wool Road, with another village planned near the Tianjara Falls.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":12\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article230660019|title=TOWNSHIP OF TIANJARA.|date=1842-01-07|work=New South Wales Government Gazette (Sydney, NSW : 1832 - 1900)|access-date=2019-01-17|pages=13}}</ref><ref name=\":21\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article230660162|title=TOWNSHIP OF NARRIGA.|date=1842-01-14|work=New South Wales Government Gazette (Sydney, NSW : 1832 - 1900)|access-date=2019-01-17|pages=54}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article230102477|title=TOWNSHIPS ON ROAD TO JERVIS BAY.|date=1843-01-13|work=New South Wales Government Gazette (Sydney, NSW : 1832 - 1900)|access-date=2019-01-17|pages=72}}</ref> The settlement to be known as 'Narriga' was to be located at the road's crossing point on the Endrick River,<ref name=\":21\" /> some distance further east and at a lower elevation than the modern-day village of Nerriga.\n\n=== Difficulties and decline ===\nSydney wool merchants and shipping interests, and businesses along the road to Sydney, were opposed to the road and the new port. Soon after the road opened, in January 1842, an anonymous report of difficulties using it appeared, which included a prediction that, ''\"it is doubtful if ever it will be completed and when finished, a constant thoroughfare to the sea coast; inasmuch as the route is chiefly barren scrub, and badly watered.\"''<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article226356874|title=COUNTRY NEWS.|date=1842-01-08|work=Sydney Free Press (NSW : 1841 - 1842)|access-date=2019-02-02|pages=2}}</ref> A year later, in January 1843, an article in the [[The Sydney Morning Herald|Sydney Morning Herald]] stated that, ''\"The township, the wharf, and the road, have all still to contend against the evil reports which have been so industriously clrculated respecting them by interested parties\"''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12413192|title=&quot;JERVIS BAY.|date=1843-01-11|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-09|pages=2}}</ref> There was some factual basis for such negative views.\n\nGeographic and economic difficulties affected The Wool Road and these, rather than the 'evil reports', caused it to fall into disuse after a relatively short time.\n\nThe steep descent proved a problem for the cumbersome [[Bullocky|bullock drays]] of the day. Although the distance was short, the slowness of the fully laden bullock drays descending the steep route led to ships being delayed at Jervis Bay and on at least one occasion leaving without taking on a cargo there. With hindsight, the route of The Wool Road via the Wandean Gap had been a poor choice; far better routes for roads over the coastal escarpment would be found later.\n\nThe truth about the road\u2014and the country through which it ran\u2014was very much contrary to the apparently exaggerated claims that had been made, when town allotments in South Huskisson had been sold for high prices in 1841.<ref name=\":15\" /> The country atop the Pidgeon House Range was infertile land that was unsuitable to provide grazing for the bullock teams, with the exception of the natural clearing at Yerock (or Yarrock) Flat\u2014known as McKenzie's Paddock<ref>{{Cite book|title=Sassafras : the story of the Post Town at Sassafras Mountain on the old Wool Road in the County of St. Vincent|last=Charles.|first=Snedden, Robert|date=1996|publisher=R C Snedden|isbn=0646259822|location=Duffy, A.C.T.|pages=22 & 24|oclc=38411506}}</ref>\u2014and the nearby area of volcanic soil around [[Sassafras, New South Wales|Sassafras]]. Fodder had to be carried. Water was also limited.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jervisbaymaritimemuseum.blogspot.com/2015/03/the-rise-and-fall-of-south-huskisson.html|title=Lady Denman Museum: The Rise and Fall of South Huskisson|last=Museum|first=Jervis Bay Maritime|date=2015-03-27|website=Lady Denman Museum|access-date=2019-01-10}}</ref> The planned villages along the route did not eventuate. The wharf at South Huskisson, although viable, was small when compared to the numerous wharves of Sydney Harbour.\n\nThe Wool Road was used for wool grown around Nerriga and Braidwood but it proved to be impractical for those places further away, like [[Government House, Canberra#History of the site|Yarralumla]]<ref>{{Cite book|title=Sassafras : the story of the Post Town at Sassafras Mountain on the old Wool Road in the County of St. Vincent|last=Charles.|first=Snedden, Robert|date=1996|publisher=R C Snedden|isbn=0646259822|location=Duffy, A.C.T.|pages=24|oclc=38411506}}</ref> and the [[Monaro (New South Wales)|Monaro]] beyond. As a result, some of those who had supported the building of the road, such as Terence Aubrey Murray, did not use it once it was completed. In late 1843, it was advertised that wool could be shipped to Sydney from the new port of [[Boydtown, New South Wales|Boydtown]] on [[Twofold Bay]].<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12414258|title=Advertising|date=1843-11-17|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2019-01-21|pages=1}}</ref> Although in time the port of Boydtown too would be a failure, it was in competition for wool cargoes with the port of South Huskisson,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article8756181|title=Domestic Intelligence.|date=1845-02-18|work=Colonial Times (Hobart, Tas. : 1828 - 1857)|access-date=2019-01-21|pages=3}}</ref> and it lay much closer by land to the Monaro. The absence of wool cargoes from the outer areas meant that the volume of wool shipped via The Wool Road and its port was much less than had been expected.\n\nThe road needed regular maintenance work and repair, especially after wet weather, to keep it open. Money became short when New South Wales entered an [[Economic history of Australia#1821\u20131880|economic depression in the 1840s]]. The causes of the depression were complex; it was probably triggered by a lengthy drought in the period 1839-1841.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12415167|title=REVIEW.|date=1844-03-27|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-10|pages=4}}</ref>\u2014which reduced wool production<ref name=\":4\" />\u2014followed by falls in the prices of wool and sheep,<ref name=\":20\" /> and was exacerbated by the [[Convicts in Australia#Cessation of transportation|cessation of convict transportation in 1840]]\u2014the assignment of new convicts to private service ended on 21 July 1841<ref name=\":8\" />\u2014which created a shortage of low-cost labour,<ref name=\":8\" /> at a time when landholders and business people had significant debts. In 1842, there were numerous insolvencies and in 1843 some bank failures.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12414843|title=COUNCIL PAPERS.|date=1843-11-21|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-10|pages=4}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12415820|title=The Sydney Morning Herald.|date=1843-05-06|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-10|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nBeing privately owned, the port and The Wool Road received no assistance from the government.<ref name=\":4\" /> By June 1842, some of the people who had subscribed to fund the building of the road could not meet their commitments to pay costs already incurred in its construction.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12875951|title=LEGISLATIVE COUNCIL.|date=1842-06-30|work=Sydney Herald (NSW : 1831 - 1842)|access-date=2019-02-02|pages=2}}</ref> A petition was made in October 1843 to recoup from the government a quarter of the  \u00a32400 in debts that had been incurred to build the road and quay to that date.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12418699|title=LEGISLATIVE COUNCIL|date=1843-10-26|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2019-01-17|pages=2}}</ref> This may indicate that the backers of the road and port were already in financial difficulty.\n\nTwo main backers of the road and port, John McKenzie of Nerriga and [[Thomas Braidwood Wilson|Dr. Thomas Wilson]] of Braidwood, were ruined financially during the 1840s depression,<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|title=Sassafras : the story of the Post Town at Sassafras Mountain on the old Wool Road in the County of St. Vincent|last=Charles.|first=Snedden, Robert|date=1996|publisher=R C Snedden|isbn=0646259822|location=Duffy, A.C.T.|pages=30|oclc=38411506}}</ref> Wilson died in November 1843\u2014[[Thomas Braidwood Wilson#Death and grave site|probably by his own hand]]\u2014leaving debts of \u00a315,264 with a deficiency of \u00a314,439,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article673427|title=INSOLVENCY PROCEEDINGS.|date=1845-05-17|work=Maitland Mercury and Hunter River General Advertiser (NSW : 1843 - 1893)|access-date=2019-02-02|pages=2}}</ref> colossal sums at that time. McKenzie lost all his land and, in 1853, was reduced to asking permission to live in a house in South Huskisson belonging to [[Edward Deas Thomson|Edward Deas Thompson]].<ref name=\":10\" />\n\nIt had been envisaged that wool would be exported direct to England from the port at South Huskisson<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article32191580|title=SOUTH HUSKISSON\u2014JERVIS BAY.|date=1841-11-29|work=Sydney Monitor and Commercial Advertiser (NSW : 1838 - 1841)|access-date=2018-12-08|pages=2}}</ref> but the port more typically was serviced by coastal steamers. Any wool carried by these steamers needed to be transhipped for export at Sydney. Shipping operators were only interested in servicing Jervis Bay, if the trade was profitable.<ref name=\":17\" /> By late 1843, some woolgrowers had found that the coastal sea freight costs were too high to justify using Jervis Bay, and were again taking their wool by bullock dray over the land route to Sydney,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12426869|title=SALE OF LAND.|date=1843-11-15|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-09|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nThe first wool auction in Sydney was held by [[Thomas Sutcliffe Mort|T.S. Mort]] in 1843<ref name=\":18\" /><ref>Interpretive signage in the small museum display about the wool industry at the 'Big Merino', Goulburn, N.S.W. (accessed November 2018)</ref> Soon afterwards, [[Samuel Lyons]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article664719|title=SYDNEY NEWS.|date=1844-02-10|work=Maitland Mercury and Hunter River General Advertiser (NSW : 1843\u20131893)|access-date=15 May 2019|pages=4}}</ref> and other Sydney auctioneers<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12414720|title=Advertising|date=2 April 1844|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842\u20131954)|access-date=15 May 2019|pages=4}}</ref> also entered the wool auction business, and the practice rapidly became widespread. The introduction of the [[Wool bale#Sale of wool|wool auction system]]\u2014and the better prices that could be obtained\u2014had the result of increasing the dominance of Sydney as the export port for wool, because the wool had to be sent first to Sydney to be auctioned.\n\nThe ''Sophia Jane'' was still calling at Jervis Bay in early June 1844<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12413641|title=COASTERS OUTWARDS.|date=1844-06-08|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-10|pages=2}}</ref> but in mid-June it went only as far as Wollongong,<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article161165173|title=COASTERS OUTWARDS.|date=1844-06-15|work=Shipping Gazette and Sydney General Trade List (NSW : 1844\u20131860)|access-date=2018-12-09|pages=90}}</ref> and after that seems to have been on the run to [[Morpeth, New South Wales|Morpeth]]. Although small coastal ships still visited the port, the days of South Huskisson as a major port had ended and no more wool was loaded there after December 1843.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12414884|title=COASTERS INWARDS.|date=1843-12-12|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-11|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nThe steep part of The Wool Road, passing through the Wandean Gap and on to Wandandian, fell into disuse and became overgrown in parts, as early as 1848.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=http://home.exetel.com.au/tomerong/history2/index_files/Page1214.htm|title=The Roads|website=home.exetel.com.au|access-date=2018-12-11}}</ref> In 1854, the road to Jervis Bay\u2014The Wool Road\u2014was described as being in a state of \"''total abandonment''\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12955991|title=BRAIDWOOD.|date=1854-09-16|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-09|pages=3}}</ref>\n\nThe last portion of the road from Wandandian to South Huskisson (now Vincentia) seemed to remain in local use but only in parts, as private roads and tracks across private land.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article226764881|title=NOTIFICATION OF PROPOSED OPENING OF ROAD.|date=1910-07-13|work=Government Gazette of the State of New South Wales (Sydney, NSW : 1901 - 2001)|access-date=2018-11-25|pages=3816}}</ref>\n\nThe decline of the port town was rapid. South Huskisson was described by a visitor in 1851 as a ''\"village on a small scale\"''. and of its buildings it was said that ''\"some of them still stand\"''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article251532298|title=A SOUTHERN EXCURSION.|date=1851-10-11|work=People's Advocate and New South Wales Vindicator (Sydney, NSW : 1848-1856)|access-date=2019-01-14|pages=6}}</ref> The town allotments in the private township of South Huskisson\u2014and the nearby 'government town' of Huskisson\u2014essentially had become worthless, by the mid-1850s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12974418|title=JERVIS BAY.|date=1856-03-12|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2019-01-14|pages=8}}</ref> By 1867, South Huskisson was deserted<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article15003935|title=THE TERMINUS.|date=1908-10-13|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-08|pages=7}}</ref>\u2014any buildings were just ruins by 1885<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article70985803|title=Jervis Bay.|date=1885-10-31|work=Australian Town and Country Journal (Sydney, NSW : 1870 - 1907)|access-date=2018-12-08|pages=26}}</ref>\u2014and, by the early 1930s, all that remained of 'the old township' was a solitary [[Araucaria heterophylla|Norfolk Island Pine.]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article16983764|title=HUSKISSON. Past and Present|last=|first=|date=1933-03-11|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-08|pages=9}}</ref>\n\n== Realignment and alternative routes ==\n[[File:Nerriga Road.jpg|thumb|261x261px|Braidwood Road (1856 route) ascending the escarpment east of Nerriga, in 2006, prior to its upgrading to modern highway standard. The cliff face shown survives, alongside the upgraded road.<ref>{{Citation|last=davo318|title=Super Tenere up the Bulee Gap|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3yfMhJYTxnA|access-date=2019-01-27}}</ref> This location is just a little west of where the 1856 and 1841 routes merged at Bulee Gap.]]\nThe [[New South Wales gold rush|discovery of gold]] in the Braidwood ([[Majors Creek, New South Wales|Major's Creek]]), [[Araluen, New South Wales|Araluen]] and Nerriga areas in the early 1850s provided an impetus for better roads to the coast.<ref>{{Cite book|title=From bullocks to bypass : a local history of the NSW south coast village of Tomerong|last=1965-|first=Blair, Margaret|date=2000|publisher=M. Blair|isbn=0646403257|location=Tomerong, N.S.W.|pages=47, 48|oclc=223017561}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12943784|title=NEWS FROM THE INTERIOR.|date=1853-02-19|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2019-01-13|pages=3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12950280|title=BRAIDWOOD.|date=1853-11-10|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-09|pages=5}}</ref>\n[[File:Bulee Gap (1841 route of The Wool Road).jpg|thumb|193x193px|Bulee Gap\u2014Man-made cutting viewed from where the 1841 route merged with the 1856 road. (February 2019).]]\nIn 1856, The Wool Road was realigned\u2014based on a new survey by George Legge\u2014to bypass the steep Bulee Gap section and continued, as a new branch off the original 1841 route, via [[Nowra Hill]] to a wharf at [[Terara]]\u2014just east of modern-day [[Nowra, New South Wales|Nowra]]\u2014on the tidal part of the [[Shoalhaven River]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Sassafras : the story of the Post Town at Sassafras Mountain on the old Wool Road in the County of St. Vincent|last=Charles.|first=Snedden, Robert|date=1996|publisher=R C Snedden|isbn=0646259822|location=Duffy, A.C.T.|pages=29|oclc=38411506}}</ref> The new road included a bridge across the Endrick River<ref name=\":11\" /> and its elevation decreased gradually from Sassafrass to Nowra. This 1856 government road became the modern day Braidwood Road (MR92). It was capable of being used by bullock drays and wool, in loads of between 24 and 50 bales, was transported over it to Nowra until the early years of the 20th century.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Nerriga on the wool road|last=Pam.|first=Radowitz|date=1990|publisher=Nerriga Historical Museum|others=Nerriga Historical Museum.|isbn=0646006010|location=[Nerriga, N.S.W.]|pages=19, 20|oclc=27515653}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Sassafras : the story of the Post Town at Sassafras Mountain on the old Wool Road in the County of St. Vincent|last=Charles.|first=Snedden, Robert|date=1996|publisher=R C Snedden|isbn=0646259822|location=Duffy, A.C.T.|pages=57|oclc=38411506}}</ref> From the line of the new Braidwood Road, another new road\u2014built in the late 1860s<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article60853055|title=GOVERNMENT GAZETTE NOTICES.|date=1868-05-11|work=Empire (Sydney, NSW : 1850 - 1875)|access-date=2018-12-08|pages=3}}</ref> and known as 'the Turpentine Road'\u2014branched eastward to [[Tomerong]]. It still provides a much gentler gradient to Jervis Bay, on a route to the north of the older and steeper 1841 Wool Road that passed through the Wandean Gap.\n\nThe Clyde Road\u2014first used in early 1858 and later a part of the [[Kings Highway (Australia)|King's Highway]]\u2014was built from Braidwood, via [[Clyde Mountain]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article136438846|title=THE CLYDE ROAD.|date=1858-01-25|work=Illawarra Mercury (Wollongong, NSW : 1856 - 1950)|access-date=2018-12-09|pages=2}}</ref> and following a line surveyed by [[Thomas Mitchell (explorer)|Sir Thomas Mitchell]]  in 1855, to the [[Clyde River (New South Wales)|Clyde River]] at [[Nelligen, New South Wales|Nelligen]], which became a port.  Another road to the coast\u2014the Araluen Road\u2014was built from Araluen to [[Moruya, New South Wales|Moruya]], in 1867-1868.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article60846232|title=PROGRESS OF PUBLIC WORKS.|date=1867-10-23|work=Empire (Sydney, NSW : 1850 - 1875)|access-date=2019-01-13|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Main Southern railway line, New South Wales|Main Southern railway line]] and other rail lines were constructed in the second half of the 19th century, confining bullock drays to transporting wool from outlying areas to the new railheads, particularly [[Goulburn, New South Wales|Goulburn]] (after 1869) from where the wool could be carried quickly to Sydney. Before the railway was extended beyond Goulburn, the town had sixty carriers delivering to the railhead.<ref>Interpretive signage at Goulburn Railway Station (accessed Nov. 2018).</ref> In 1893, the [[South Coast railway line, New South Wales|South Coast railway line]] reached [[Bomaderry railway station|Bomaderry]], just north of Nowra, providing a second railhead.\n\nA section of the original The Wool Road from Nerriga that passed through the Bulee Gap cutting was bypassed by the 1856 route but it remained in use as an alternative [[stock route]] to the corresponding part to the newer Braidwood Road. During the Second World War, a part of this section of the original road was deliberately destroyed using explosives, to limit access by an enemy to the inland area and the national capital, [[Canberra]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Nerriga on the wool road|last=Pam.|first=Radowitz|date=1990|publisher=Nerriga Historical Museum|others=Nerriga Historical Museum.|isbn=0646006010|location=[Nerriga, N.S.W.]|pages=22|oclc=27515653}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy and remnants ==\nOne surviving section of the original 1841 Wool Road is located just north of the existing Braidwood Road (MR92), near to the Bulee Gap, east of Nerriga. The man-made Bulee Gap cutting\u2014bypassed by the 1856 route\u2014and the surviving sections of original road passing through it, are remnants of the 1841 convict-built road. (A part of the original road immediately north of the Bulee Gap cutting was deliberately and thoroughly destroyed during WWII.) The existing Braidwood Road (MR92), east of Bulee Gap, largely follows the original 1841 route of The Wool Road but the section of the current road west of the Bullee Gap largely follows the 1856 realignment.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://stgeorgesbasin.info/level2/heritage.html|title=St Georges Basin Heritage|website=stgeorgesbasin.info|access-date=2019-02-27}}</ref>\n[[File:Braidwood Road (1856 route) at junction with 1841 route at Bulee Gap.jpg|thumb|192x192px|Braidwood Road (1856 route). Preserved section of 1856 road near where it merged with the older (1841) Wool Road that emerged from the Bulee Gap cutting (shown in the centre background). (February 2019)]]\n\nWhen assessed in 2002, the Braidwood Road west of the Bulee Gap showed some remnants of the 1856 roadworks and was an example of road making from the immediate post-convict period, before the formation of the Department of Public Works in 1859. Drill marks were visible in the sandstone outcrops where they have been cut by the roadmakers. [[Dry stone]] retaining walls were evident, some of which had been compromised by modern road grading.<ref name=\":1\" /> Between 2007 and 2010, the Braidwood Road was [[Sealed road|sealed]] and upgraded to modern highway standard at a cost of $99-million,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rms.nsw.gov.au/documents/about/corporatepublications/2010-11-rta-ar-full.pdf|title=2010-11 Annual Report|last=NSW Roads & Traffic Authority|date=2011|pages=26, 27}}</ref> including major work where the road climbs from the Endrick River and passes the Bulee Gap<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.southcoastregister.com.au/story/1002014/bulee-gap-takes-centre-stage/|title=Bulee Gap takes centre stage|date=2009-09-15|website=South Coast Register|language=en|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref> The work in that area included removing bends, cutting back the cliff faces,  installing high retaining walls and building a four-span concrete bridge structure. The route of the modern road over the bridge structure preserved sandstone landforms and a part of the 1856 road's formation, including a [[dry stone]] walled embankment and the junction with the older 1841 route at the south end of the Bulee Gap cutting.[[File:Wandean Gap - Start of descent of 1841 Wool Road in February 2019.jpg|thumb|193x193px|Wandean Gap\u2014Wandean Road (1841 Wool Road) at the start of the steep descent.(February 2019)]]The last portion of the road to South Huskisson (now Vincentia) was reopened as a public road around 1911-12 and that involved the resumption of some private land\u2014land being used at the time as 'private road' or 'private track'\u2014to do so (South Huskisson\u2014now Vincentia\u2014was, at that time, still a 'private town').<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article230685906|title=NOTIFICATION UNDER THE PUBLIC ROADS ACT OF 1902, OF RESUMPTION AND DEDICATION OF LANDS FOR ROADS, AND PARTS OF ROADS DECLARED TO RE A PUBLIC ROAD.|last=|first=|date=1911-08-30|work=Government Gazette of the State of New South Wales (Sydney, NSW : 1901 - 2001)|access-date=2018-11-25|pages=4779}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article161470101|title=Advertising|date=1912-04-27|work=Ulladulla and Milton Times (NSW : 1891 - 1917)|access-date=2018-12-02|pages=4}}</ref> The modern road is known as The Wool Road and is a largely straight road. To the south of the modern Wool Road\u2014starting at Island Point Road and following a more circuititous route south of Cockrow Creek\u2014is 'The Old Wool Road' and connecting it to the modern day The Wool Road is 'Wool Lane' . Where it exists, this 'Old Wool Road' is closer to the route of the original road than the corresponding section of the modern straighter road. \nHistorically, the end of The Wool Road was where it entered the town of South Huskisson,<ref name=\":9\" /> from where the streets of the town led to a wharf on Jervis Bay; the modern day road known as The Wool Road now ends at a roundabout intersecting Elizabeth Drive and Burton Street, Vincentia, near the shore of Jervis Bay. Some hewn sandstone blocks from the 1842 wharf are visible at low tide near the Holden Street boat ramp<ref name=\":4\" /> Many street names from \"The Old Township\" are still in use in Vincentia today and much of the original street plan remains.<ref name=\":9\" /> The 'government town' north of Moona Moona Creek, which was surveyed at the same time as \"the Old Township\",<ref name=\":9\" /> grew from the early 1860s onwards to become modern-day [[Huskisson, New South Wales|Huskisson]].\n\nThere is a lookout known as the [[Jerrawangala]] Lookout and to reach it visitors turn off Braidwood Road and pass over part of the 1841 route, along the first part of modern-day Wandean Road. The 1841 route of The Wool Road passes through the Wandean Gap approximately 500m to the north from the location of the modern day lookout. The elevation of the lookout demonstrates the folly of building a road through the escarpment at this location. Drill marks in the rocks at Wandean Gap are remnants of the construction of The Wool Road in 1841.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://stgeorgesbasin.info/level2/heritage.html|title=St Georges Basin Heritage|website=stgeorgesbasin.info|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref>\n\nThe little used road through the Wandean Gap to Wandandian (Wandean Road) still exists; most of it is single-lane and unsealed and much of it is unsuitable for general traffic. Adventurous drivers using four wheel drive vehicles can still use this route.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Kings Highway (Australia)|King's Highway]] (an alternative route to the coast built in the 1850s)\n* [[Great North Road (New South Wales)|Great North Road]] (another convict-built road in New South Wales)\n*[[Oxley Highway#History|Oxley Highway]] (originally a convict-built road for transporting wool from [[Walcha, New South Wales|Walcha]] to the coast at [[Port Macquarie]])\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.nationalparks.nsw.gov.au/things-to-do/lookouts/jerrawangala-lookout/visitor-info#Maps-and-downloads/ NSW NPWS Jerrawangala Lookout]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5eDu7z9OweM/ Wandean Rd Wandanian: A video by Bob James showing travel from Braidwood Road to Wandandian. The Wandean Gap section is shown between 3:50 and 4:40.]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3yfMhJYTxnA Modern Braidwood Road to Bulee Gap: A video showing Endrick River crossing (1:06 to 1:09) and bridge that aligns with location of Bulee Gap cutting (2:32 to 2:37)]\n\n[[Category:Historical roads of New South Wales]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date = November 2019}}\n'''The Wool Road''' (also later known as 'The Old Wool Road') was a [[Historic roads|historic road]] of New South Wales, Australia, that ran from [[Nerriga, New South Wales|Nerriga]] to what is now [[Vincentia, New South Wales|Vincentia]] on [[Jervis Bay]]. It was constructed privately in 1841, using convict labour. Its purpose was to provide a shorter route to a seaport for wool grown at [[Braidwood, New South Wales|Braidwood]] and beyond.\n\nThe historical significance of The Wool Road is that it was the first road, capable of being used by wheeled vehicles, linking the inland area around [[Braidwood, New South Wales|Braidwood]] to the [[South Coast (New South Wales)|South Coast]]. The road led to the foundation of the privately-owned port town of South Huskisson (called [[Vincentia, New South Wales|Vincentia]] since 1952) and the adjacent 'government townshIp' of [[Huskisson, New South Wales|Huskisson]].\n\nThe Wool Road's route made its use difficult and the port on Jervis Bay was not a success. In 1856, the original road was realigned and extended to [[Terara]] (near [[Nowra, New South Wales|Nowra]]) instead of Jervis Bay, becoming the Braidwood Road. The old route through the coastal escarpment to Jervis Bay fell into disuse for many years.\n\nMuch of the original route of The Wool Road remains in use today but some parts are accessible only to four-wheel drive traffic. Only a part of the original route that is currently in use is known as The Wool Road or The Old Wool Road today\u2014the section from the Princes Highway to Vincentia. The remainder of the original route still in use today is made up of a significant part of the Braidwood Road (MR92), Wandean Road, and a short section of the Princes Highway.[[File:Wandean Gap - Bottom of First Sideling of 1841 Wool Road in February 2019.jpg|thumb|256x256px|Wandean Gap - The bottom of the first of three steep sidelings on  Wandean Road (1841 Wool Road) that take it from the plateau of the Pigeon House Range to the ridge-line sloping toward the coast. (February 2019) ]]\n== Historical context ==\n[[File:Wandandian tool-sharpening grooves near Wool Road route outside Vincentia (April 2019).jpg|thumb|282x282px|Tool-sharpening groves made by  Wandandian people, in sandstone rock nearby the route of The Wool Road, outside Vincentia, N.S.W. (April 2019)]]\nThe land between Nerriga and Jervis Bay is part of the country of the [[Wandandian people]], a group of the [[Yuin]]. The [[Wandandian people]],<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://ro.uow.edu.au/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1007&context=uowbooks|title=Illawarra and South Coast Aborigines 1770-1850|last=Organ|first=Michael|date=1990|publisher=Aboriginal Education Unit Wollongong University|page=401|isbn=086418-112-4}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Aboriginal Tribes of Australia|last=Tindale|first=N.B.|publisher=University of California Press|year=1974|isbn=|location=Berkeley|pages=}}</ref> spoke Dharamba,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collection.aiatsis.gov.au/austlang/language/s56|title=S56: Dharamba|website=collection.aiatsis.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref> which was probably the northernmost dialect of the [[Dhurga language]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/dharawaldhurgala0000eade/page/4|title=The Dharawal and Dhurga languages of the New South Wales South Coast|last=Eades|first=Diana|date=1976|publisher=Australian Institute of Aboriginal Studies|isbn=0855750510|location=Canberra|pages=[https://archive.org/details/dharawaldhurgala0000eade/page/4 4, 5, 6]|oclc=2948202}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collection.aiatsis.gov.au/austlang/language/s53|title=S53: Dhurga|website=collection.aiatsis.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2019-02-27}}</ref> Traditionally, the [[Wandandian people]] used paths, from the Pigeon House Range through the area now known as [[Wandandian, New South Wales|Wandandian]], to reach the fishing grounds of [[St Georges Basin (New South Wales)|St George's Basin]] and the inland hunting areas of the tablelands. In the 1830s and 1840s, the Wandandian people still lived on their traditional lands.\n\nThe land also lay within the [[St Vincent County|County of St. Vincent]], one of the [[Nineteen Counties]] in which white settlement was permitted by the colonial government of New South Wales. In the late 1820s and 1830s colonial settlement had spread to the vicinity of [[Lake George (New South Wales)|Lake George]], [[Braidwood, New South Wales|Braidwood]], [[Yass, New South Wales|Yass]], the Limestone Plains (now [[Canberra]]), and beyond to the [[Monaro (New South Wales)|Monaro district]]. The country settled was well-suited for the production of wool, for which there was a booming export market, but lay far from the existing port of Sydney. Transporting the [[wool bale]]s using the cumbersome [[Bullocky|bullock drays]] of the time involved a long and arduous journey from Braidwood\u2014taking around three weeks at the bullock's slow pace and with their need to stop for rest, feeding and watering\u2014via [[Bungonia, New South Wales|Bungonia]] and [[Goulburn, New South Wales|Goulburn]] to Sydney. The owner of [[Government House, Canberra#History of the site|Yarralumla]], [[Terence Aubrey Murray|Terence Murray]], further away at the Limestone Plains, complained that, in wet weather, the drays could take as long as three months to reach Sydney.<ref>{{Citation|last=Wilson|first=Gwendoline|title=Murray, Sir Terence Aubrey (1810\u20131873)|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/murray-sir-terence-aubrey-2498|work=Australian Dictionary of Biography|publisher=National Centre of Biography, Australian National University|access-date=2018-12-11}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1830s, a bridle-track known as the Corn Trail was made, from [[Clyde Mountain]] to the coastal [[Buckenbowra River|Buckenbowra Valley]], but it was steep and only usable by pack horses. Transport of wool in [[Wool bale|bales]] required a road that could be used by bullock drays.\n\nJervis Bay, a large sheltered bay that was suitable as a deepwater port lay far closer than Sydney but there was no road from Braidwood toward the coast beyond Nerriga. From 1831, there were sea-going auxiliary steamships\u2014such as the ''[[Sophia Jane]]''\u2014operating in New South Wales but steam powered railways were not in place before the mid-1850s.\n\nAlthough transportation of [[Convicts in Australia|convicts]] to New South Wales had ceased in 1840, it was still a penal colony. Convicts were a workforce that could be put to work on roadmaking.\n\n== Route ==\n[[File:Tianjara Creek looking north from Tianjara falls.jpg|thumb|209x209px|The valley of Tianjara Creek, looking north from Tianjara Falls. The  Wool Road passed south of the top of the falls to avoid this valley and the nearby valley of the Clyde River.]]\nThe endpoints of The Wool Road were the village of [[Nerriga, New South Wales|Nerriga]]\u2014by 1841 already connected to Braidwood by a rudimentary road\u2014and the newly created port of South Huskisson (later known as 'the old township' and today known as [[Vincentia, New South Wales|Vincentia]]) on Jervis Bay. The significant geographical obstacles to be overcome were crossing the [[Endrick River]] near Nerriga, climbing to a plateau in the northern part of the Pigeon House Range, then avoiding the steep valleys and gorges cut into that plateau by tributaries of the [[Shoalhaven River|Shoalhaven]] and [[Clyde River (New South Wales)|Clyde]] rivers, and subsequently descending from the plateau to the coastal plain to reach Jervis Bay.\n\nAfter fording the Endrick River, The Wool Road broadly followed the direction of the modern-day Braidwood Road (MR92), from Nerriga to near the Boolijah Peak, a point east of [[Sassafras, New South Wales|Sassafras]]. The current Braidwood Road alignment is the result of an upgrade in 1856. The original 1841 road's exact route was different in some places, most significantly where it climbs the Pigeon House Range at Bulee Mountain near Nerriga. The 1841 road traversed the ridge to the north of Bulee Mountain and went through the man-made Bulee Gap,<ref name=\":5\" />  whereas the 1856 alignment and the current road pass to the south of Bulee Mountain[[File:Sussex Inlet from Jerrawangala lookout.jpg|thumb|View from Jerrawangala lookout atop the coastal escarpment approx. 500m south of Wandean Gap. St George's Basin is visible in the centre and beyond it,  to its left, in the far distance, is Jervis Bay.|202x202px]]Following the line of the modern Braidwood Road, the road crested the Pigeon House Range, at a location known as Billy's Hill. It then passed over the narrow part of the plateau not cut by the impassable gorges of Ettrema Creek (and Bainbrig Creek It continued past [[Sassafras, New South Wales|Sassafras]] and the Tianjara Falls, through another narrow part of the plateau, between the impassable valleys of [[Tianjara|Tianjara Creek]] and the most upstream parts of the [[Clyde River (New South Wales)|Clyde River]].\n\nFrom near the Boolijah Peak, The Wool Road diverged from the current route of the Braidwood Road and followed the route of modern-day Wandean Road, through the steep Wandean Gap.<ref name=\":5\" /> (historically also known as the Jerrawangala Gap<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article229236583|title=JERVIS BAY. THE WOOL ROAD|last=|first=|date=1914-04-20|work=Sun (Sydney, NSW : 1910 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-08|pages=12}}</ref>), then following ridgelines of tributaries of Wandandian Creek, to [[Wandandian, New South Wales|Wandandian]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|title=Sassafras : the story of the Post Town at Sassafras Mountain on the old Wool Road in the County of St. Vincent|last=Charles.|first=Snedden, Robert|date=1996|publisher=R C Snedden|isbn=0646259822|location=Duffy, A.C.T.|pages=22|oclc=38411506}}</ref> In this section, the road's elevation dropped by approximately 2,500 feet in 10 miles<ref name=\":3\" /> (760m in 16&nbsp;km), as it descended the coastal escarpment, via the locality of [[Jerrawangala]] and [[Wandandian, New South Wales|Wandandian]]. Most of this part of the route is now only accessible to four-wheel drive traffic.<ref name=\":0\">{{Citation|last=Bob James|title=Wandean Rd Wandanian|date=2016-01-20|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5eDu7z9OweM|access-date=2018-11-23}} A video showing travel from Braidwood Road to Wandandian. The Wandean Gap section of the road is shown between 3:50 and 4:40.</ref>\n\nFrom Wandandian, The Wool Road followed the route of a previous foot track\u2014already in existence by 1841<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=http://stgeorgesbasin.info/level3/larmer%20report.html|title=Larmer's Survey of the Wool Road|website=stgeorgesbasin.info|access-date=2018-12-18}}</ref> and probably of Aboriginal origin\u2014to Jervis Bay. Its route followed the approximate line of the existing [[Princes Highway]] for a short distance (skirting north of Wandandian Creek).,<ref name=\":5\" /> then broadly followed the direction of the modern road still known as 'The Wool Road', from the modern-day Princes Highway near [[Basin View]], via [[St Georges Basin, New South Wales|St George's Basin]] to [[Vincentia, New South Wales|Vincentia]]. At St. George's Basin, the 1841 route followed the road now known as 'The Old Wool Road' where it deviates from a section of the modern-day The Wool Road that was constructed around 1929.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article213797940|title=A TRIP TO ST. GEORGE'S BASIN.|date=1929-06-28|work=Nowra Leader (NSW : 1909 - 1939)|access-date=2018-12-13|pages=8}}</ref> The Wool Road ended at a port on [[Jervis Bay]] that is now Vincentia.\n\n== History ==\n=== Finding the Route ===\nIn 1831, Robert Futter of [[Bungonia, New South Wales|Bungonia]] and George Galbraith of Nerriga formed an expedition to find a path from Nerriga to Jervis Bay. The others making up the expedition were William Ryrie, [[James Holman]]\u2014who was known as the 'Blind Traveller'\u2014and two Aboriginal guides<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|title=Sassafras : the story of the Post Town at Sassafras Mountain on the old Wool Road in the County of St. Vincent|last=Charles.|first=Snedden, Robert|date=1996|publisher=R C Snedden|isbn=0646259822|location=Duffy, A.C.T.|pages=19|oclc=38411506}}</ref> whose names are not known.\n\nHolman later recounted\u2014in his book  ''\u2018A Voyage Round The World: Including Travels In Africa, Asia, Australia, America Etc. From 1827 - 1832' ,'' published in 1834-1835 \u2014that the route they had taken from Yerock Flat (west of Sassafras Mountain) to the coast was taken against the advice of the Aboriginal guides, who had strongly suggested following the range further to the north. Holman later recognised that had they done so they could have found a far easier route for a road to Jervis Bay<ref name=\":6\" /> (such as that of the longer but less steep Turpentine Road). However, the explorers had passed through rugged and difficult country and, having reached Jervis Bay via what was apparently the shortest route, did not search for any longer but easier route.\n\nIn 1839, the owner of [[Yarralumla, Australian Capital Territory#Settlement|Yarralumla]], [[Terence Aubrey Murray]], also explored a route between Nerriga and Jervis Bay, which may have been similar to that followed by the Futter expedition.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Nerriga on the wool road|last=Pam.|first=Radowitz|date=1990|publisher=Nerriga Historical Museum|others=Nerriga Historical Museum.|isbn=0646006010|location=[Nerriga, N.S.W.]|pages=19|oclc=27515653}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article31726503|title=Country News.|date=1839-09-27|work=Australasian Chronicle (Sydney, NSW : 1839 - 1843)|access-date=2019-01-09|pages=4}}</ref>\n\n=== Proponents ===\nAfter at first failing to obtain government funding for such a road in 1839,<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article31724219|title=The Colonist.|date=1839-12-18|work=Colonist (Sydney, NSW : 1835 - 1840)|access-date=2019-01-13|pages=2}}</ref> landholders from around Braidwood and Nerriga decided to build their own road from Nerriga to Jervis Bay. The principal advocates and financial backers for the new road were Colonel John McKenzie of Nerriga and [[Thomas Braidwood Wilson|Dr. Thomas Braidwood Wilson]] of Braidwood. Wealthy and influential colonists [[Terence Aubrey Murray]], [[Alexander Berry]], [[Robert Campbell (1769\u20131846)|Robert Campbell]], [[Thomas Walker (philanthropist)|Thomas Walker]] and [[James Macarthur (politician)|James Macarthur]] were also supporters of the new road.<ref name=\":16\" />\n\n[[Edward Deas Thomson|Edward Deas Thompson]]\u2014at the time the [[Chief Secretary of New South Wales|Colonial Secretary of New South Wales]]\u2014stood to benefit from the construction of the road. He owned 2,560 acres of otherwise useless land on the western shore of Jervis Bay south of Moona Moona Creek,<ref name=\":13\" /> where an east-facing point\u2014now known as Plantation Point\u2014provided shelter from the south and a safe port\u2014the 'Inner Harbour'\u2014and a port township could be situated.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n=== Survey ===\nThe route of the new road was surveyed by a government surveyor, James Larmer, who delivered his final report on the route in August 1840. Larmer advocated the same basic route followed by the Futter and Murray expeditions and\u2014apparently in ignorance\u2014dismissed any route descending to the coast further north than his surveyed line. His report reads, ''\"In conclusion I beg to add that on so great an extent of Road less obstructions and difficulties in the formation could not be met on any other line of Road of the same extent in the Colony\u2014and from enquiries I have made both from whites and Aboriginals and from my own observations I am fully convinced that it would be impossible to discover a more practicable line than the one now Surveyed. On the North it is a bold and continuous range but totally unfit for Drays to pass down to the Coast\u2014and on the South numerous deep rocky gullies that are impassable.\"''<ref name=\":12\" />\n\n=== Construction ===\nSeventy convicts were assigned to Nerriga landowner Colonel John McKenzie, under the command of [[John Coghill (Australian politician)|Captain John Coghill]], in February 1841, and work commenced.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite book|title=Sassafras : the story of the Post Town at Sassafras Mountain on the old Wool Road in the County of St. Vincent|last=Charles.|first=Snedden, Robert|date=1996|publisher=R C Snedden|isbn=0646259822|location=Duffy, A.C.T.|pages=21, 22|oclc=38411506}}</ref>  In June 1841, another fourteen men, to work on the road, arrived at the new port of South Huskisson aboard the steamer ''Tamar''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12869734|title=DEPARTURE.|date=1841-06-21|work=Sydney Herald (NSW : 1831 - 1842)|access-date=2019-01-12|pages=2}}</ref> The Bulee Gap was created by blasting away a narrow neck of sandstone rock to bring the road onto the plateau of the Pigeon House Range. Blasting was also needed to create a pass for the descent through the Wandean Gap. The Wool Road covered a distance of approximately 37 miles (60&nbsp;km) and it was built at an estimated cost of \u00a3997.<ref name=\":1\" /> As the road neared completion, the road gang became a nuisance at the Jervis Bay end of the road; a report stated that, ''\"Scenes of debauchery and violence are of daily occurrence, there being no magistrate or constable to control them.\"''<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article31732606|title=Court of Quarter Sessions.|date=1841-08-17|work=Australasian Chronicle (Sydney, NSW : 1839 - 1843)|access-date=2019-02-27|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nThe road from Nerriga to the coast was completed in October 1841.<ref name=\":14\" />  In 1842, the existing road linking Nerriga to Braidwood was substantially upgraded, also using convict labour assigned to Colonel John Mackenzie.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rms.nsw.gov.au/documents/projects/south-coast/charleyong-bridge/charleyong-bridge-ref-appendix-f.pdf|title=Appendix F - Statement of Heritage Impact CHARLEYONG BRIDGE REPLACEMENT|last=ngh environmental|date=25 July 2017|pages=8, 9}}</ref> By late 1842 there was a road capable of taking wheeled traffic from Braidwood and beyond to Jervis Bay.\n\n=== Heyday ===\nThe first cargo of wool from Nerriga was carried over The Wool Road and loaded at South Huskisson in late 1841. At first, the drays were taken to the beach and the wool bales were carried out on small boats to a waiting ship<ref name=\":4\" />  but, after a company was formed to do so\u2014in March 1842 <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12874445|title=Advertising|date=1842-03-30|work=Sydney Herald (NSW : 1831 - 1842)|access-date=2019-01-16|pages=1}}</ref>\u2014a wharf was built<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12425035|title=JERVIS BAY.|date=1842-12-08|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-08|pages=3}}</ref> during late 1842.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12421643|title=MECHANICS' SCHOOL OF ARTS.|date=1842-09-16|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2019-01-16|pages=2}}</ref> The auxiliary steamship ''[[Sophia Jane]]'' made her first trip to the port of South Huskisson in June 1841<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article228246600|title=Shipping Intelligence.|date=1841-06-23|work=Free Press and Commercial Journal (Sydney, NSW : 1841)|access-date=2019-01-09|pages=2}}</ref> and provided a monthly<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12876234|title=Advertising|date=1842-07-19|work=Sydney Herald (NSW : 1831 - 1842)|access-date=2019-01-16|pages=1}}</ref> and at times twice monthly service between the port and Sydney.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://jervisbaymaritimemuseum.blogspot.com/2014/08/steamer-for-jervis-bay-sophia-jane.html|title=Lady Denman Museum: Steamer for Jervis Bay \u2013 the Sophia Jane.|last=Museum|first=Jervis Bay Maritime|date=2014-08-05|website=Lady Denman Museum|access-date=2018-12-08}}</ref> The barque ''Cygnet'' visited the port in December 1842 to load a cargo of wool for London.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12417944|title=COASTERS OUTWARDS.|date=1842-12-14|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-09|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nThe town of South Huskisson<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-229901982|title=Sketch of the township of South Huskisson [cartographic material].|website=nla.gov.au|language=en|access-date=2018-12-08}}</ref> grew around the port, located on land granted in 1830 to [[Edward Deas Thomson|Edward Deas Thompson]].<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article2216540|title=Classified Advertising|date=1834-07-05|work=Sydney Gazette and New South Wales Advertiser (NSW : 1803 - 1842)|access-date=2018-12-18|pages=4}}</ref> A wool store capable of storing 2,000 [[Wool bale|bales of wool]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12872568|title=Advertising|date=1841-12-01|work=Sydney Herald (NSW : 1831 - 1842)|access-date=2019-01-16|pages=1}}</ref> and an inn were built. At least 200 building allotments in the private township were sold<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article229241439|title=JERVIS BAY. CITY OF THE PAST.|last=|first=|date=1914-04-06|work=Sun (Sydney, NSW : 1910 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-08|pages=6}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article32189562|title=SOUTH HUSKISSON\u2014JERVIS BAY.|date=1841-06-18|work=Sydney Monitor and Commercial Advertiser (NSW : 1838 - 1841)|access-date=2019-01-16|pages=3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article2555128|title=Classified Advertising|date=1841-11-27|work=Sydney Gazette and New South Wales Advertiser (NSW : 1803 - 1842)|access-date=2018-12-08|pages=3}}</ref> during 1841, at high prices<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article36851732|title=No title|date=1841-06-22|work=Australian (Sydney, NSW : 1824 - 1848)|access-date=2019-01-12|pages=2}}</ref> on an assumption of the success of the road and port, and in anticipation of large future capital gains.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article2553637|title=Classified Advertising|date=1841-06-17|work=Sydney Gazette and New South Wales Advertiser (NSW : 1803 - 1842)|access-date=2019-01-12|pages=1}}</ref> The total of the prices of the 100 allotments sold in June 1841 was \u00a33,519.<ref name=\":19\" />\n\nA 'government township' was also surveyed to the north of Moona Moona Creek, which became [[Huskisson, New South Wales|Huskisson]].<ref name=\":9\" /> Allotments were sold in Huskisson in February 1843.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12413758|title=SALE OF TOWN ALLOTMENTS.|date=1843-01-18|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2019-02-26|pages=4}}</ref> Five villages were planned, as stops for bullock teams along The Wool Road, with another village planned near the Tianjara Falls.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":12\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article230660019|title=TOWNSHIP OF TIANJARA.|date=1842-01-07|work=New South Wales Government Gazette (Sydney, NSW : 1832 - 1900)|access-date=2019-01-17|pages=13}}</ref><ref name=\":21\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article230660162|title=TOWNSHIP OF NARRIGA.|date=1842-01-14|work=New South Wales Government Gazette (Sydney, NSW : 1832 - 1900)|access-date=2019-01-17|pages=54}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article230102477|title=TOWNSHIPS ON ROAD TO JERVIS BAY.|date=1843-01-13|work=New South Wales Government Gazette (Sydney, NSW : 1832 - 1900)|access-date=2019-01-17|pages=72}}</ref> The settlement to be known as 'Narriga' was to be located at the road's crossing point on the Endrick River, <ref name=\":21\" /> some distance further east and at a lower elevation than the modern-day village of Nerriga.\n\n=== Difficulties and decline ===\nSydney wool merchants and shipping interests, and businesses along the road to Sydney, were opposed to the road and the new port. Soon after the road opened, in January 1842, an anonymous report of difficulties using it appeared, which included a prediction that, ''\"it is doubtful if ever it will be completed and when finished, a constant thoroughfare to the sea coast; inasmuch as the route is chiefly barren scrub, and badly watered.\"''<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article226356874|title=COUNTRY NEWS.|date=1842-01-08|work=Sydney Free Press (NSW : 1841 - 1842)|access-date=2019-02-02|pages=2}}</ref> A year later, in January 1843, an article in the [[The Sydney Morning Herald|Sydney Morning Herald]] stated that, ''\"The township, the wharf, and the road, have all still to contend against the evil reports which have been so industriously clrculated respecting them by interested parties\"''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12413192|title=&quot;JERVIS BAY.|date=1843-01-11|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-09|pages=2}}</ref> There was some factual basis for such negative views.\n\nGeographic and economic difficulties affected The Wool Road and these, rather than the 'evil reports', caused it to fall into disuse after a relatively short time.\n\nThe steep descent proved a problem for the cumbersome [[Bullocky|bullock drays]] of the day. Although the distance was short, the slowness of the fully laden bullock drays descending the steep route led to ships being delayed at Jervis Bay and on at least one occasion leaving without taking on a cargo there. With hindsight, the route of The Wool Road via the Wandean Gap had been a poor choice; far better routes for roads over the coastal escarpment would be found later.\n\nThe truth about the road\u2014and the country through which it ran\u2014was very much contrary to the apparently exaggerated claims that had been made, when town allotments in South Huskisson had been sold for high prices in 1841.<ref name=\":15\" /> The country atop the Pidgeon House Range was infertile land that was unsuitable to provide grazing for the bullock teams, with the exception of the natural clearing at Yerock (or Yarrock) Flat\u2014known as McKenzie's Paddock<ref>{{Cite book|title=Sassafras : the story of the Post Town at Sassafras Mountain on the old Wool Road in the County of St. Vincent|last=Charles.|first=Snedden, Robert|date=1996|publisher=R C Snedden|isbn=0646259822|location=Duffy, A.C.T.|pages=22 & 24|oclc=38411506}}</ref>\u2014and the nearby area of volcanic soil around [[Sassafras, New South Wales|Sassafras]]. Fodder had to be carried. Water was also limited.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jervisbaymaritimemuseum.blogspot.com/2015/03/the-rise-and-fall-of-south-huskisson.html|title=Lady Denman Museum: The Rise and Fall of South Huskisson|last=Museum|first=Jervis Bay Maritime|date=2015-03-27|website=Lady Denman Museum|access-date=2019-01-10}}</ref> The planned villages along the route did not eventuate. The wharf at South Huskisson, although viable, was small when compared to the numerous wharves of Sydney Harbour.\n\nThe Wool Road was used for wool grown around Nerriga and Braidwood but it proved to be impractical for those places further away, like [[Government House, Canberra#History of the site|Yarralumla]]<ref>{{Cite book|title=Sassafras : the story of the Post Town at Sassafras Mountain on the old Wool Road in the County of St. Vincent|last=Charles.|first=Snedden, Robert|date=1996|publisher=R C Snedden|isbn=0646259822|location=Duffy, A.C.T.|pages=24|oclc=38411506}}</ref> and the [[Monaro (New South Wales)|Monaro]] beyond. As a result, some of those who had supported the building of the road, such as Terence Aubrey Murray, did not use it once it was completed. In late 1843, it was advertised that wool could be shipped to Sydney from the new port of [[Boydtown, New South Wales|Boydtown]] on [[Twofold Bay]].<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12414258|title=Advertising|date=1843-11-17|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2019-01-21|pages=1}}</ref> Although in time the port of Boydtown too would be a failure, it was in competition for wool cargoes with the port of South Huskisson,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article8756181|title=Domestic Intelligence.|date=1845-02-18|work=Colonial Times (Hobart, Tas. : 1828 - 1857)|access-date=2019-01-21|pages=3}}</ref> and it lay much closer by land to the Monaro. The absence of wool cargoes from the outer areas meant that the volume of wool shipped via The Wool Road and its port was much less than had been expected.\n\nThe road needed regular maintenance work and repair, especially after wet weather, to keep it open. Money became short when New South Wales entered an [[Economic history of Australia#1821\u20131880|economic depression in the 1840s]]. The causes of the depression were complex; it was probably triggered by a lengthy drought in the period 1839-1841.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12415167|title=REVIEW.|date=1844-03-27|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-10|pages=4}}</ref>\u2014which reduced wool production<ref name=\":4\" />\u2014followed by falls in the prices of wool and sheep,<ref name=\":20\" /> and was exacerbated by the [[Convicts in Australia#Cessation of transportation|cessation of convict transportation in 1840]]\u2014the assignment of new convicts to private service ended on 21 July 1841<ref name=\":8\" />\u2014which created a shortage of low-cost labour,<ref name=\":8\" /> at a time when landholders and business people had significant debts. In 1842, there were numerous insolvencies and in 1843 some bank failures.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12414843|title=COUNCIL PAPERS.|date=1843-11-21|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-10|pages=4}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12415820|title=The Sydney Morning Herald.|date=1843-05-06|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-10|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nBeing privately owned, the port and The Wool Road received no assistance from the government.<ref name=\":4\" /> By June 1842, some of the people who had subscribed to fund the building of the road could not meet their commitments to pay costs already incurred in its construction.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12875951|title=LEGISLATIVE COUNCIL.|date=1842-06-30|work=Sydney Herald (NSW : 1831 - 1842)|access-date=2019-02-02|pages=2}}</ref> A petition was made in October 1843 to recoup from the government a quarter of the  \u00a32400 in debts that had been incurred to build the road and quay to that date.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12418699|title=LEGISLATIVE COUNCIL|date=1843-10-26|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2019-01-17|pages=2}}</ref> This may indicate that the backers of the road and port were already in financial difficulty. \n\nTwo main backers of the road and port, John McKenzie of Nerriga and [[Thomas Braidwood Wilson|Dr. Thomas Wilson]] of Braidwood, were ruined financially during the 1840s depression,<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|title=Sassafras : the story of the Post Town at Sassafras Mountain on the old Wool Road in the County of St. Vincent|last=Charles.|first=Snedden, Robert|date=1996|publisher=R C Snedden|isbn=0646259822|location=Duffy, A.C.T.|pages=30|oclc=38411506}}</ref> Wilson died in November 1843\u2014[[Thomas Braidwood Wilson#Death and grave site|probably by his own hand]]\u2014leaving debts of \u00a315,264 with a deficiency of \u00a314,439,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article673427|title=INSOLVENCY PROCEEDINGS.|date=1845-05-17|work=Maitland Mercury and Hunter River General Advertiser (NSW : 1843 - 1893)|access-date=2019-02-02|pages=2}}</ref> colossal sums at that time. McKenzie lost all his land and, in 1853, was reduced to asking permission to live in a house in South Huskisson belonging to [[Edward Deas Thomson|Edward Deas Thompson]].<ref name=\":10\" />\n\nIt had been envisaged that wool would be exported direct to England from the port at South Huskisson<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article32191580|title=SOUTH HUSKISSON\u2014JERVIS BAY.|date=1841-11-29|work=Sydney Monitor and Commercial Advertiser (NSW : 1838 - 1841)|access-date=2018-12-08|pages=2}}</ref> but the port more typically was serviced by coastal steamers. Any wool carried by these steamers needed to be transhipped for export at Sydney. Shipping operators were only interested in servicing Jervis Bay, if the trade was profitable.<ref name=\":17\" /> By late 1843, some woolgrowers had found that the coastal sea freight costs were too high to justify using Jervis Bay, and were again taking their wool by bullock dray over the land route to Sydney,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12426869|title=SALE OF LAND.|date=1843-11-15|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-09|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nThe first wool auction in Sydney was held by [[Thomas Sutcliffe Mort|T.S. Mort]] in 1843<ref name=\":18\" /><ref>Interpretive signage in the small museum display about the wool industry at the 'Big Merino', Goulburn, N.S.W. (accessed November 2018)</ref> Soon afterwards, [[Samuel Lyons]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article664719|title=SYDNEY NEWS.|date=1844-02-10|work=Maitland Mercury and Hunter River General Advertiser (NSW : 1843\u20131893)|access-date=15 May 2019|pages=4}}</ref> and other Sydney auctioneers<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12414720|title=Advertising|date=2 April 1844|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842\u20131954)|access-date=15 May 2019|pages=4}}</ref> also entered the wool auction business, and the practice rapidly became widespread. The introduction of the [[Wool bale#Sale of wool|wool auction system]]\u2014and the better prices that could be obtained\u2014had the result of increasing the dominance of Sydney as the export port for wool, because the wool had to be sent first to Sydney to be auctioned.\n\nThe ''Sophia Jane'' was still calling at Jervis Bay in early June 1844<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12413641|title=COASTERS OUTWARDS.|date=1844-06-08|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-10|pages=2}}</ref> but in mid-June it went only as far as Wollongong,<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article161165173|title=COASTERS OUTWARDS.|date=1844-06-15|work=Shipping Gazette and Sydney General Trade List (NSW : 1844\u20131860)|access-date=2018-12-09|pages=90}}</ref> and after that seems to have been on the run to [[Morpeth, New South Wales|Morpeth]]. Although small coastal ships still visited the port, the days of South Huskisson as a major port had ended and no more wool was loaded there after December 1843.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12414884|title=COASTERS INWARDS.|date=1843-12-12|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-11|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nThe steep part of The Wool Road, passing through the Wandean Gap and on to Wandandian, fell into disuse and became overgrown in parts, as early as 1848.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=http://home.exetel.com.au/tomerong/history2/index_files/Page1214.htm|title=The Roads|website=home.exetel.com.au|access-date=2018-12-11}}</ref> In 1854, the road to Jervis Bay\u2014The Wool Road\u2014was described as being in a state of \"''total abandonment''\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12955991|title=BRAIDWOOD.|date=1854-09-16|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-09|pages=3}}</ref>\n\nThe last portion of the road from Wandandian to South Huskisson (now Vincentia) seemed to remain in local use but only in parts, as private roads and tracks across private land.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article226764881|title=NOTIFICATION OF PROPOSED OPENING OF ROAD.|date=1910-07-13|work=Government Gazette of the State of New South Wales (Sydney, NSW : 1901 - 2001)|access-date=2018-11-25|pages=3816}}</ref>\n\nThe decline of the port town was rapid. South Huskisson was described by a visitor in 1851 as a ''\"villiage on a small scale\"''. and of its buildings it was said that ''\"some of them still stand\"''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article251532298|title=A SOUTHERN EXCURSION.|date=1851-10-11|work=People's Advocate and New South Wales Vindicator (Sydney, NSW : 1848-1856)|access-date=2019-01-14|pages=6}}</ref> The town allotments in the private township of South Huskisson\u2014and the nearby 'government town' of Huskisson\u2014essentially had become worthless, by the mid-1850s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12974418|title=JERVIS BAY.|date=1856-03-12|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2019-01-14|pages=8}}</ref> By 1867, South Huskisson was deserted<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article15003935|title=THE TERMINUS.|date=1908-10-13|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-08|pages=7}}</ref>\u2014any buildings were just ruins by 1885<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article70985803|title=Jervis Bay.|date=1885-10-31|work=Australian Town and Country Journal (Sydney, NSW : 1870 - 1907)|access-date=2018-12-08|pages=26}}</ref>\u2014and, by the early 1930s, all that remained of 'the old township' was a solitary [[Araucaria heterophylla|Norfolk Island Pine.]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article16983764|title=HUSKISSON. Past and Present|last=|first=|date=1933-03-11|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-08|pages=9}}</ref>\n\n== Realignment and alternative routes ==\n[[File:Nerriga Road.jpg|thumb|261x261px|Braidwood Road (1856 route) ascending the escarpment east of Nerriga, in 2006, prior to its upgrading to modern highway standard. The cliff face shown survives, alongside the upgraded road.<ref>{{Citation|last=davo318|title=Super Tenere up the Bulee Gap|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3yfMhJYTxnA|access-date=2019-01-27}}</ref> This location is just a little west of where the 1856 and 1841 routes merged at Bulee Gap.]]\nThe [[New South Wales gold rush|discovery of gold]] in the Braidwood ([[Majors Creek, New South Wales|Major's Creek]]), [[Araluen, New South Wales|Araluen]] and Nerriga areas in the early 1850s provided an impetus for better roads to the coast.<ref>{{Cite book|title=From bullocks to bypass : a local history of the NSW south coast village of Tomerong|last=1965-|first=Blair, Margaret|date=2000|publisher=M. Blair|isbn=0646403257|location=Tomerong, N.S.W.|pages=47, 48|oclc=223017561}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12943784|title=NEWS FROM THE INTERIOR.|date=1853-02-19|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2019-01-13|pages=3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article12950280|title=BRAIDWOOD.|date=1853-11-10|work=Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)|access-date=2018-12-09|pages=5}}</ref>\n[[File:Bulee Gap (1841 route of The Wool Road).jpg|thumb|193x193px|Bulee Gap\u2014Man-made cutting viewed from where the 1841 route merged with the 1856 road. (February 2019).]]\nIn 1856, The Wool Road was realigned\u2014based on a new survey by George Legge\u2014to bypass the steep Bulee Gap section and continued, as a new branch off the original 1841 route, via [[Nowra Hill]] to a wharf at [[Terara]]\u2014just east of modern-day [[Nowra, New South Wales|Nowra]]\u2014on the tidal part of the [[Shoalhaven River]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Sassafras : the story of the Post Town at Sassafras Mountain on the old Wool Road in the County of St. Vincent|last=Charles.|first=Snedden, Robert|date=1996|publisher=R C Snedden|isbn=0646259822|location=Duffy, A.C.T.|pages=29|oclc=38411506}}</ref> The new road included a bridge across the Endrick River<ref name=\":11\" /> and its elevation decreased gradually from Sassafrass to Nowra. This 1856 government road became the modern day Braidwood Road (MR92). It was capable of being used by bullock drays and wool, in loads of between 24 and 50 bales, was transported over it to Nowra until the early years of the 20th century.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Nerriga on the wool road|last=Pam.|first=Radowitz|date=1990|publisher=Nerriga Historical Museum|others=Nerriga Historical Museum.|isbn=0646006010|location=[Nerriga, N.S.W.]|pages=19, 20|oclc=27515653}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Sassafras : the story of the Post Town at Sassafras Mountain on the old Wool Road in the County of St. Vincent|last=Charles.|first=Snedden, Robert|date=1996|publisher=R C Snedden|isbn=0646259822|location=Duffy, A.C.T.|pages=57|oclc=38411506}}</ref> From the line of the new Braidwood Road, another new road\u2014built in the late 1860s<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article60853055|title=GOVERNMENT GAZETTE NOTICES.|date=1868-05-11|work=Empire (Sydney, NSW : 1850 - 1875)|access-date=2018-12-08|pages=3}}</ref> and known as 'the Turpentine Road'\u2014branched eastward to [[Tomerong]]. It still provides a much gentler gradient to Jervis Bay, on a route to the north of the older and steeper 1841 Wool Road that passed through the Wandean Gap.\n\nThe Clyde Road\u2014first used in early 1858 and later a part of the [[Kings Highway (Australia)|King's Highway]]\u2014was built from Braidwood, via [[Clyde Mountain]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article136438846|title=THE CLYDE ROAD.|date=1858-01-25|work=Illawarra Mercury (Wollongong, NSW : 1856 - 1950)|access-date=2018-12-09|pages=2}}</ref> and following a line surveyed by [[Thomas Mitchell (explorer)|Sir Thomas Mitchell]]  in 1855, to the [[Clyde River (New South Wales)|Clyde River]] at [[Nelligen, New South Wales|Nelligen]], which became a port.  Another road to the coast\u2014the Araluen Road\u2014was built from Araluen to [[Moruya, New South Wales|Moruya]], in 1867-1868.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article60846232|title=PROGRESS OF PUBLIC WORKS.|date=1867-10-23|work=Empire (Sydney, NSW : 1850 - 1875)|access-date=2019-01-13|pages=2}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Main Southern railway line, New South Wales|Main Southern railway line]] and other rail lines were constructed in the second half of the 19th century, confining bullock drays to transporting wool from outlying areas to the new railheads, particularly [[Goulburn, New South Wales|Goulburn]] (after 1869) from where the wool could be carried quickly to Sydney. Before the railway was extended beyond Goulburn, the town had sixty carriers delivering to the railhead.<ref>Interpretive signage at Goulburn Railway Station (accessed Nov. 2018).</ref> In 1893, the [[South Coast railway line, New South Wales|South Coast railway line]] reached [[Bomaderry railway station|Bomaderry]], just north of Nowra, providing a second railhead.\n\nA section of the original The Wool Road from Nerriga that passed through the Bulee Gap cutting was bypassed by the 1856 route but it remained in use as an alternative [[stock route]] to the corresponding part to the newer Braidwood Road. During the Second World War, a part of this section of the original road was deliberately destroyed using explosives, to limit access by an enemy to the inland area and the national capital, [[Canberra]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Nerriga on the wool road|last=Pam.|first=Radowitz|date=1990|publisher=Nerriga Historical Museum|others=Nerriga Historical Museum.|isbn=0646006010|location=[Nerriga, N.S.W.]|pages=22|oclc=27515653}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy and remnants ==\nOne surviving section of the original 1841 Wool Road is located just north of the existing Braidwood Road (MR92), near to the Bulee Gap, east of Nerriga. The man-made Bulee Gap cutting\u2014bypassed by the 1856 route\u2014and the surviving sections of original road passing through it, are remnants of the 1841 convict-built road. (A part of the original road immediately north of the Bulee Gap cutting was deliberately and thoroughly destroyed during WWII.) The existing Braidwood Road (MR92), east of Bulee Gap, largely follows the original 1841 route of The Wool Road but the section of the current road west of the Bullee Gap largely follows the 1856 realignment.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://stgeorgesbasin.info/level2/heritage.html|title=St Georges Basin Heritage|website=stgeorgesbasin.info|access-date=2019-02-27}}</ref>\n[[File:Braidwood Road (1856 route) at junction with 1841 route at Bulee Gap.jpg|thumb|192x192px|Braidwood Road (1856 route). Preserved section of 1856 road near where it merged with the older (1841) Wool Road that emerged from the Bulee Gap cutting (shown in the centre background). (February 2019)]]\n\nWhen assessed in 2002, the Braidwood Road west of the Bulee Gap showed some remnants of the 1856 roadworks and was an example of road making from the immediate post-convict period, before the formation of the Department of Public Works in 1859. Drill marks were visible in the sandstone outcrops where they have been cut by the roadmakers. [[Dry stone]] retaining walls were evident, some of which had been compromised by modern road grading.<ref name=\":1\" /> Between 2007 and 2010, the Braidwood Road was [[Sealed road|sealed]] and upgraded to modern highway standard at a cost of $99-million,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rms.nsw.gov.au/documents/about/corporatepublications/2010-11-rta-ar-full.pdf|title=2010-11 Annual Report|last=NSW Roads & Traffic Authority|date=2011|pages=26, 27}}</ref> including major work where the road climbs from the Endrick River and passes the Bulee Gap<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.southcoastregister.com.au/story/1002014/bulee-gap-takes-centre-stage/|title=Bulee Gap takes centre stage|date=2009-09-15|website=South Coast Register|language=en|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref> The work in that area included removing bends, cutting back the cliff faces,  installing high retaining walls and building a four-span concrete bridge structure. The route of the modern road over the bridge structure preserved sandstone landforms and a part of the 1856 road's formation, including a [[dry stone]] walled embankment and the junction with the older 1841 route at the south end of the Bulee Gap cutting.[[File:Wandean Gap - Start of descent of 1841 Wool Road in February 2019.jpg|thumb|193x193px|Wandean Gap\u2014Wandean Road (1841 Wool Road) at the start of the steep descent.(February 2019)]]The last portion of the road to South Huskisson (now Vincentia) was reopened as a public road around 1911-12 and that involved the resumption of some private land\u2014land being used at the time as 'private road' or 'private track'\u2014to do so (South Huskisson\u2014now Vincentia\u2014was, at that time, still a 'private town').<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article230685906|title=NOTIFICATION UNDER THE PUBLIC ROADS ACT OF 1902, OF RESUMPTION AND DEDICATION OF LANDS FOR ROADS, AND PARTS OF ROADS DECLARED TO RE A PUBLIC ROAD.|last=|first=|date=1911-08-30|work=Government Gazette of the State of New South Wales (Sydney, NSW : 1901 - 2001)|access-date=2018-11-25|pages=4779}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article161470101|title=Advertising|date=1912-04-27|work=Ulladulla and Milton Times (NSW : 1891 - 1917)|access-date=2018-12-02|pages=4}}</ref> The modern road is known as The Wool Road and is a largely straight road. To the south of the modern Wool Road\u2014starting at Island Point Road and following a more circuititous route south of Cockrow Creek\u2014is 'The Old Wool Road' and connecting it to the modern day The Wool Road is 'Wool Lane' . Where it exists, this 'Old Wool Road' is closer to the route of the original road than the corresponding section of the modern straighter road. \nHistorically, the end of The Wool Road was where it entered the town of South Huskisson,<ref name=\":9\" /> from where the streets of the town led to a wharf on Jervis Bay; the modern day road known as The Wool Road now ends at a roundabout intersecting Elizabeth Drive and Burton Street, Vincentia, near the shore of Jervis Bay. Some hewn sandstone blocks from the 1842 wharf are visible at low tide near the Holden Street boat ramp<ref name=\":4\" /> Many street names from \"The Old Township\" are still in use in Vincentia today and much of the original street plan remains.<ref name=\":9\" /> The 'government town' north of Moona Moona Creek, which was surveyed at the same time as \"the Old Township\",<ref name=\":9\" /> grew from the early 1860s onwards to become modern-day [[Huskisson, New South Wales|Huskisson]].\n\nThere is a lookout known as the [[Jerrawangala]] Lookout and to reach it visitors turn off Braidwood Road and pass over part of the 1841 route, along the first part of modern-day Wandean Road. The 1841 route of The Wool Road passes through the Wandean Gap approximately 500m to the north from the location of the modern day lookout. The elevation of the lookout demonstrates the folly of building a road through the escarpment at this location. Drill marks in the rocks at Wandean Gap are remnants of the construction of The Wool Road in 1841.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://stgeorgesbasin.info/level2/heritage.html|title=St Georges Basin Heritage|website=stgeorgesbasin.info|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref>\n\nThe little used road through the Wandean Gap to Wandandian (Wandean Road) still exists; most of it is single-lane and unsealed and much of it is unsuitable for general traffic. Adventurous drivers using four wheel drive vehicles can still use this route.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Kings Highway (Australia)|King's Highway]] (an alternative route to the coast built in the 1850s)\n* [[Great North Road (New South Wales)|Great North Road]] (another convict-built road in New South Wales)\n*[[Oxley Highway#History|Oxley Highway]] (originally a convict-built road for transporting wool from [[Walcha, New South Wales|Walcha]] to the coast at [[Port Macquarie]])\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.nationalparks.nsw.gov.au/things-to-do/lookouts/jerrawangala-lookout/visitor-info#Maps-and-downloads/ NSW NPWS Jerrawangala Lookout]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5eDu7z9OweM/ Wandean Rd Wandanian: A video by Bob James showing travel from Braidwood Road to Wandandian. The Wandean Gap section is shown between 3:50 and 4:40.]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3yfMhJYTxnA Modern Braidwood Road to Bulee Gap: A video showing Endrick River crossing (1:06 to 1:09) and bridge that aligns with location of Bulee Gap cutting (2:32 to 2:37)]\n\n[[Category:Historical roads of New South Wales]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: villiage \u2192 village per source", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Wool_Road_(New_South_Wales)"}
{"title_page": "HAL HJT-36 Sitara", "text_new": "<!-- This article is a part of [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft]]. Please see [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Aircraft/page content]] for recommended layout. -->\n{|{{Infobox aircraft begin\n |name = HJT-36 ''Sitara''\n |image = File:Hindustan HJT-36 Sitara Krivchikov 2007.jpg\n |caption = \n}}\n{{Infobox aircraft type\n |type = Intermediate Trainer\n |manufacturer = [[Hindustan Aeronautics Limited]]\n |designer =\n |first flight = 7 March 2003\n |introduced =\n |retired =\n |primary user = [[Indian Air Force]]\n |more users= [[Indian Navy]]\n |number built = 13<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/hal-s-intermediate-jet-trainer-flies-again-after-extensive-re-design-119041900219_1.html|title=HAL\u2019s intermediate trainer flies again, reviving prospect of all-indigenous trainer fleet|date=19 April 2019|publisher=Business-standard}}</ref>\n |status = Limited series production\n |unit cost =\n |variants with their own articles =\n}}\n|}\n\nThe '''HAL HJT-36 ''Sitara''''' ([[IAST|Sit\u0101r\u0101]]: \"''[[star]]''\") is a subsonic intermediate jet [[trainer aircraft]] developed by [[Hindustan Aeronautics Limited]] (HAL) for the [[Indian Air Force]] and the [[Indian Navy]]. The HJT-36 will replace the HAL [[HJT-16 Kiran|HJT-16 ''Kiran'']] as the Stage-2 trainer for the two forces.\n\nThe ''Sitara'' is a conventional jet trainer with low swept wings, tandem cockpit and small air intakes for the engine on either side of its fuselage. It entered limited series production by 2010 but according to the Indian Air Force officials it remains \"unfit\" for service due to technological issues related to spin test (as of March 2017).<ref name=\"Bedi Jane's\">{{cite web|last1=Bedi|first1=Rahul|title=India's HJT-36 Sitara remains 'unfit' for use as intermediate jet trainer|url=http://www.janes.com/article/68386/india-s-hjt-36-sitara-remains-unfit-for-use-as-intermediate-jet-trainer|website=Jane's 360|publisher=IHS|accessdate=27 July 2017}}</ref> In April 2019, ''Sitara'' flew for the first time in three years with a modified air frame to correct its spin characteristics.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Waldron |first1=Greg |title=PICTURES: HAL HJT-36 IJT flies after three year hiatus |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/pictures-hal-hjt-36-ijt-flies-after-three-year-hia-457570/ |work=Flightglobal.com |date=18 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Development==\n[[File:IJT Prototype in hangar.jpg|thumb|Prototype IJT in its hangar at [[Hindustan Aeronautics Limited]]|alt=|left]]\n\nHAL started design work on an intermediate jet trainer in 1997. The concept was developed as a successor to HAL's earlier trainer, the HJT-16 ''Kiran'', introduced in 1968. In 1999, following reviews by the Indian Air Force, the [[Government of India]] awarded HAL a contract for development, testing and certification of two prototype IJT aircraft.\n\nThe first and second prototypes of the HJT-36, labelled PT-1 and PT-2, flew on 7 March 2003 and in March 2004, respectively. The program was then delayed with the Air Force assessing the [[SNECMA Turbomeca Larzac]] engine, with 14.1&nbsp;kN of thrust, as under-powered. In response, in August 2005, HAL reached a deal to replace the SNECMA engine with the [[NPO Saturn]] AL-55I with 16.9&nbsp;kN of thrust. The deal also provided for license-production of the engine in India by HAL.<ref name=at-hjt>http://www.airforce-technology.com/projects/hjttrainer/{{Unreliable source?|reason=domain on WP:BLACKLIST|date=June 2016}}</ref>\n\nFurther delays were caused by delays in delivery of the NPO Saturn engine by 2 years, as well as due to two accidents in February 2007 and in February 2009 involving each of the prototypes, which grounded the aircraft for repairs and investigations.<ref name=hindu-aero2007>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/Jet-trainer-overshoots-runway-at-aero-show/article14717982.ece|title=Jet trainer overshoots runway at aero show|date=9 February 2007|publisher=|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref><ref name=ad-hjt>{{cite web|url=https://www.blogger.com/blogin.g?blogspotURL=http%3A%2F%2Ftheasiandefence.blogspot.com%2F2009%2F02%2Fintermediate-jet-trainer-lands-on-belly.html&bpli=1|title=Login to read|website=www.blogger.com}}</ref>\n\nThe first AL-55I engine was received from [[Russia]] on 28 December 2008, 2 years later than committed, and was installed on PT-1.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/Russian-engines-coming-today-for-intermediate-jet-trainer/article15369375.ece|title=Russian engines coming today for intermediate jet trainer|date=28 December 2008|publisher=|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref> Following ground taxiing trials, flight tests with the new engine started on 9 May 2009.<ref name=deagel>{{cite web|url=http://www.deagel.com/Combat-Aircraft/IJT_a000076001.aspx|title=IJT|website=www.deagel.com}}</ref><ref name=\"hindu.com\">{{cite news| url=http://www.hindu.com/2009/05/14/stories/2009051454651800.htm |title=HAL\u2019s intermediate jet trainer HJT-36 makes maiden flight with Russian engine  |date=14 May 2009 |accessdate=12 July 2010 |location=Chennai, India |work=The Hindu}}</ref>\n\nAfter further development and extensive testing, the [[Indian Air Force]] placed an order for 73 aircraft. After over 280 test flights, the aircraft entered limited series production in 2009 for the first 12 aircraft to be delivered to the Air Force. The first flight test for the limited series aircraft occurred in January 2010,<ref name=aw-20100528>{{cite web|last1=Krishnan|first1=Anantha|title=India Thought Leaders: HAL Chairman Sets Firm Agenda For Aggressive Export Sales|url=http://aviationweek.com/awin/india-thought-leaders-hal-chairman-sets-firm-agenda-aggressive-export-sales|website=aviationweek.com|language=en|date=28 May 2010}}</ref> and [[initial operational capability]] was expected by July 2011.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/news-by-industry/transportation/airlines-/-aviation/indigenous-jet-trainer-to-get-initial-clearance-by-july/articleshow/7468968.cms | work=The Times Of India | title=Indigenous jet trainer to get initial clearance by July | date=10 February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://img196.imageshack.us/img196/1378/hal3.jpg|title=Vayu aerospace article|publisher=}}</ref> The Air Force order was expected to grow to over 200 aircraft. The third Prototype in development phase. On 27 July 2012 it performed first Engine Ground Run.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hal-india.com/MSM/VOL-5_MSM-94.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=26 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116061900/http://hal-india.com/MSM/VOL-5_MSM-94.pdf |archive-date=16 January 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref Name=\"Public Information Bureau, India\">{{cite web|url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/erelease.aspx?relid=93617|title=Press Information Bureau|website=pib.nic.in}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, HAL declared that Sitara was 'weeks' from certification.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/in-tejas-shadow-sitara-trainer-also-poised-to-enter-service-113122000026_1.html|title=In Tejas' shadow, Sitara trainer also poised to enter service|first=Ajai|last=Shukla|date=20 December 2013|publisher=|via=Business Standard}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 February 2014 the Indian MOD submitted a statement that the development of IJT was in the advanced stages of certification, with more than 800 test flights completed so far. The activities were progressing well with completion of sea level trials, night flying trials, high altitude trials as well as weapon and drop tank trials. The activities left for obtaining Final Operational Clearance (FOC) are the refinement of stall characteristics, and spin testing which will be commenced as soon as stall characteristics were refined. All efforts were being made to achieve FOC by December 2014. Production of aircraft was to commence immediately thereafter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livefistdefence.com/2014/02/hjt-36-target-foc-by-dec-2014-says-mod.html|title=HJT-36 Target FOC By Dec 2014, Says MoD|first=Shiv|last=Aroor|publisher=}}</ref> However the stall cannot be tested until HAL redesigns the entire aircraft to correct its \"inherent asymmetry\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://indrus.in/blogs/2014/02/24/flameout_why_the_iaf_wont_accept_hals_jet_trainer_33117.html |title=Flameout: Why the IAF won't accept HAL\u2019s jet trainer |last1=Simha |first1=Rakesh Krishnan |date=24 February 2014 |website=indrus.in |publisher=\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 |accessdate=23 February 2014}}</ref> BAE was consulted on certain design changes, specifically the tail.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/defence/spin-trials-to-revive-intermediate-jet-trainer-programme-soon/articleshow/56209445.cms|title=Spin trials to revive intermediate jet trainer programme soon|first=Manu|last=Pubby|date=14 July 2018|publisher=|via=The Economic Times}}</ref> Afterwards the design was put to mathematical and wind tunnel tests. The modified aircraft was expected to complete the spin tests by September 2015, and the production of 85 aircraft for the Indian Air Force to begin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/iafs-ijt-set-for-spin-test/article7631349.ece|title=IAF\u2019s IJT set for spin test|first=Madhumathi|last=D.s|date=9 September 2015|publisher=|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref> \n\nIn March 2017, [[Jane's Information Group|Jane's]] reported that due to the HJT-36's \"unresolvable\" issues associated with critical stall and spin characteristics the aircraft is not ready to serve as an intermediate jet trainer for Indian Air Force pilots.<ref name=\"Bedi Jane's\" /> With Birhle as a consultant, the air frame was modified to move the [[Vertical stabilizer|tailfin]] and [[tailplane]] further down which is expected to make spin recovery easier. The modified aircraft flew for the first time in April 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shukla |first1=Ajai |title=HAL's Intermediate Jet Trainer flies again after extensive re-design |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/hal-s-intermediate-jet-trainer-flies-again-after-extensive-re-design-119041900219_1.html |work=Business Standard |date=19 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Design ==\n[[File:S3466 HAL HJT-36 Sitra (8413512389).jpg|thumb|S3466 HAL HJT-36 Sitra at [[Yelahanka Air Force Station]] ]]\nHJT-36 uses light alloys and composites, with a conventional low wing design with 18\u00b0 leading edge sweepback and a 9.8m wingspan. It features a hydraulically retractable tricycle-type landing gear. The single-wheeled main units retract inward and the twin nose wheel unit retracts forward. About a quarter of the aircraft's line replaceable units are common between it and the [[HAL Tejas]] trainer variant.\n\nIn the cockpit, the HJT-36 has a conventional tandem two-seat configuration with the trainee pilot forward and the instructor in the raised seat to the rear. The single-piece canopy gives both pilots good, all-round vision. The prototype aircraft used [[NPP Zvezda|Zvezda]] K-26LT lightweight [[zero-zero ejection seat]]s. However, these may be replaced with [[Martin-Baker]] Mk.16 IN16S seats, due to a price escalation of the former.<ref name=\"supplier\">{{cite web|url=http://www.airframer.com/aircraft_detail.html?program=641|title=HAL HJT-36 Sitara - program supplier guide|website=www.airframer.com}}</ref> The pilots have both conventional and manual flight controls.<ref name=at-hjt/>\n\nThe trainer has a full glass cockpit with a layout similar to current generation combat aircraft. It uses an integrated digital avionics system from [[GE Aviation Systems]]. Head-up display and repeater is produced by [[Elbit Systems]].<ref name=supplier/>\n\nThe aircraft has five external hardpoints for weapons-training. There is one centre-line hardpoint under the fuselage and two weapon pylons under each wing for carrying rockets, gun pods and bombs. The maximum external payload is 1,000&nbsp;kg.\n\nThe prototype aircraft were initially powered by a [[SNECMA Turbomeca Larzac 04-H-20]] non-afterburning [[turbofan]] developing 14.12&nbsp;kN of thrust. All production models will use the more powerful [[NPO Saturn AL-55I]] engine with about 16.9&nbsp;kN of thrust, as stipulated by the 2005 air staff requirements from the Air Force.\n\n== Specifications (HJT-36, prototypes) ==\n[[File:Profil HAL HJT-36.png|right|300px]]\n{{Aircraft specs\n|ref=Jane's All the World's Aircraft<ref name=\"jawa-1617\">{{cite book|editor1-last=Jackson|editor1-first=Paul|editor2-last=Peacock|editor2-first=Lindsay|editor3-last=Bushell|editor3-first=Susan|editor4-last=Willis|editor4-first=David|editor5-last=Winchester|editor5-first=Jim|title=IHS Jane's All the World's Aircraft: Development & Production|date=2016\u20132017|location=Couldson|isbn=978-0710631770|page=304|chapter=India}}</ref>\n|prime units?=met<!-- imp or kts first for US aircraft, and UK aircraft pre-metrification, \nmet(ric) first for all others. You MUST choose a format, or no specifications will show -->\n<!--\n        General characteristics\n-->\n|genhide=\n\n|crew=2\n|capacity=\n|length m=11\n|length ft=36\n|length in=1\n|length note=\n|span m=10\n|span ft=32\n|span in=9.75\n|span note=\n|upper span m=\n|upper span ft=\n|upper span in=\n|upper span note=\n|mid span m=\n|mid span ft=\n|mid span in=\n|mid span note=\n|lower span m=\n|lower span ft=\n|lower span in=\n|lower span note=\n|swept m=<!-- swing-wings -->\n|swept ft=<!-- swing-wings -->\n|swept in=<!-- swing-wings -->\n|swept note=\n|dia m=<!-- airships etc -->\n|dia ft=<!-- airships etc -->\n|dia in=<!-- airships etc -->\n|dia note=\n|width m=<!-- if applicable -->\n|width ft=<!-- if applicable -->\n|width in=<!-- if applicable -->\n|width note=\n|height m=4.4\n|height ft=14\n|height in